WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:04.680
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:25.480
&gt;&gt; Karen Lloyd: Good morning.

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:27.780
I want to thank each of you
for taking the time to come

00:00:27.780 --> 00:00:29.930
to the most beautiful
building in Washington DC

00:00:29.930 --> 00:00:34.770
but most especially, to the
Coolidge Auditorium to be a part

00:00:34.770 --> 00:00:37.670
of our Veterans Day programming.

00:00:37.670 --> 00:00:39.950
As direct I'm Karen Lloyd
and I'm the director

00:00:39.950 --> 00:00:42.130
of the Veterans History Project,

00:00:42.130 --> 00:00:45.950
and as a retired army aviator
I'm also the widow, sibling

00:00:45.950 --> 00:00:47.700
and child of veterans.

00:00:47.700 --> 00:00:50.690
And I'm so pleased to welcome
you, especially the veterans,

00:00:50.690 --> 00:00:52.810
to the Library of Congress.

00:00:52.810 --> 00:00:56.310
The library makes a special
effort this week in particular

00:00:56.310 --> 00:00:59.580
to honor and recognize
veterans and their families

00:00:59.580 --> 00:01:02.960
and to explore the ways military
men and women have connected

00:01:02.960 --> 00:01:06.640
to home and family during
and after their service

00:01:06.640 --> 00:01:09.890
for World War I through
the current conflicts.

00:01:09.890 --> 00:01:12.290
We are proud to collaborate
with our colleagues

00:01:12.290 --> 00:01:16.540
from across the library to
offer a series of events titled:

00:01:16.540 --> 00:01:20.510
Coming Home Veterans Day
at the Library of Congress.

00:01:20.510 --> 00:01:22.970
In the back, you will
find his handy card --

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:27.770
With all of today's
programming's,

00:01:27.770 --> 00:01:29.070
many of which airline

00:01:29.070 --> 00:01:31.470
to are exhibited
echoes of the Great War.

00:01:31.470 --> 00:01:35.430
This exhibit examines the
upheaval of the World War

00:01:35.430 --> 00:01:39.760
as Americans confronted it,
both at home and abroad.

00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:42.600
It's located up here in
the Jefferson building

00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:45.440
and its compellingly
rendered offers glimpses

00:01:45.440 --> 00:01:49.230
of The Human Condition
Transcendence of Time and Place,

00:01:49.230 --> 00:01:51.540
in part three over
30 collections

00:01:51.540 --> 00:01:53.690
from the Veterans
History Project.

00:01:53.690 --> 00:01:56.400
I hope you'll find
time to see it.

00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:59.370
I'd also ask that you
consider taking a copy

00:01:59.370 --> 00:02:03.510
of not just this library
magazine, but also the other one

00:02:03.510 --> 00:02:08.110
that we have in the
back as you depart.

00:02:08.110 --> 00:02:09.870
It focuses in part

00:02:09.870 --> 00:02:13.220
on The Veterans History
Project and our collections.

00:02:13.220 --> 00:02:16.810
Now, a little bit about The
Veterans History Project:

00:02:16.810 --> 00:02:19.020
it provides inspiration
and instruction

00:02:19.020 --> 00:02:23.500
to foster nationwide volunteer
effort for individuals to reach

00:02:23.500 --> 00:02:27.970
out to the veterans and their
lives and listen really listen,

00:02:27.970 --> 00:02:31.680
and sending donate those
collections to the library,

00:02:31.680 --> 00:02:33.410
so that we have those
oral histories

00:02:33.410 --> 00:02:35.770
and first-person narratives.

00:02:35.770 --> 00:02:39.160
From World War I through the
current conflict Veterans

00:02:39.160 --> 00:02:42.530
like Mr. Greenwall whose
family graciously donated his

00:02:42.530 --> 00:02:45.320
interviews with the
Veterans History Project

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:48.100
and whose words come alive,
both through the exhibit

00:02:48.100 --> 00:02:52.340
and through this morning's
Porter Ale by Douglas Taurel.

00:02:52.340 --> 00:02:54.180
After the performance,
both Douglas

00:02:54.180 --> 00:02:57.770
and our senior reference
specialist Megan Harris will

00:02:57.770 --> 00:02:59.480
answer your questions.

00:02:59.480 --> 00:03:01.780
So, again thank you for
joining us joining us today

00:03:01.780 --> 00:03:04.450
and a special shout-out
to the Greenwall family

00:03:04.450 --> 00:03:06.900
who made a special effort
to come today and we are

00:03:06.900 --> 00:03:08.370
so appreciative of that.

00:03:08.370 --> 00:03:10.670
So, thank you [applauses].

