00:05:00.790 --> 00:05:07.160
I was drafted in
December 1917, my name?

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:11.680
Private first-class Irving
Greenwald E Company the 308.

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:14.030
We are part of the
77th Division.

00:05:14.030 --> 00:05:16.750
I was drafted before million
other young brave boys.

00:05:16.750 --> 00:05:22.360
Our war was called "The
War to End All Wars".

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:28.160
Just imagine that a
"War to End All Wars" --

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:33.510
it was called the Great War.

00:05:33.510 --> 00:05:44.430
[ Trumpet ]

00:05:44.430 --> 00:05:46.870
My camp [inaudible] Long Island.

00:05:46.870 --> 00:05:50.200
My day started waking up
at 5:30 a.m., for revelry,

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:52.450
drilling with the bayonet
and then, had to put on

00:05:52.450 --> 00:05:58.250
and take off a gas mask,
lectures, I will not engage

00:05:58.250 --> 00:06:01.060
in any [inaudible],
exercises and supper.

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:04.510
Supper was usually
frankfurters, sauerkraut,

00:06:04.510 --> 00:06:06.480
bread, potatoes and coffee.

00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:08.640
Lots and lots of coffee.

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:12.830
Not too bad not too good
either, but not too bad.

00:06:12.830 --> 00:06:16.710
After supper, I head to the
YMCA to buy some tobacco

00:06:16.710 --> 00:06:19.600
or have some ice cream
or to telephone Leah

00:06:19.600 --> 00:06:21.970
if I could get a line.

00:06:21.970 --> 00:06:26.810
After supper, I head back to
my bunk to do some reading

00:06:26.810 --> 00:06:30.460
or some writing, usually
a letter to Leah or momma,

00:06:30.460 --> 00:06:34.680
and I always kiss Leah's
picture before I went to bed,

00:06:34.680 --> 00:06:36.980
not before saying my
prayers of course.

00:06:43.590 --> 00:06:44.890
Can I be honest?

00:06:44.890 --> 00:06:51.060
I lay awake many nights
thinking how unfair

00:06:51.060 --> 00:06:53.050
and unkind the army was
it since it sends so many

00:06:53.050 --> 00:06:55.490
of us boys away from home.

00:06:55.490 --> 00:07:02.220
It's not really fair when
you were to think about it.

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:04.020
My favorite days at camp
were always when the passes

00:07:04.020 --> 00:07:06.100
to go home for the weekend
were posted up in the wall.

00:07:06.100 --> 00:07:10.570
I'd be so happy that I had
to run and I telephone Leah

00:07:10.570 --> 00:07:15.500
and she be so delighted that she
would just, she would just cry.

00:07:15.500 --> 00:07:21.750
My Leah, she had an angel's
face, she was graceful,

00:07:21.750 --> 00:07:28.720
and strong, she was everything,
she was everything to me.

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:31.210
My entire goal on campus was
always to come home to be

00:07:31.210 --> 00:07:33.840
with her as much as I could.

00:07:33.840 --> 00:07:35.550
When we go home for
the weekends,

00:07:35.550 --> 00:07:37.110
I take her to the theater.

00:07:37.110 --> 00:07:40.580
The theater would be
full of men in uniform,

00:07:40.580 --> 00:07:43.100
we'd always go see Jack O'
Lantern with Fred Stone,

00:07:43.100 --> 00:07:46.210
he was without a doubt
my favorite comedian.

00:07:46.210 --> 00:07:48.700
I'd always kiss her
outside the theater;

00:07:48.700 --> 00:07:53.470
you see it's not very polite
to kiss outside in public.

00:07:53.470 --> 00:07:56.140
I'd hold her in my arms
and I'd whisper to God

00:07:56.140 --> 00:07:59.450
"can you keep me home and
grant me a year peace,

00:07:59.450 --> 00:08:04.230
happiness and a healthy baby".

00:08:04.230 --> 00:08:07.640
You see, we were
going to have a child;

00:08:07.640 --> 00:08:09.690
we were going to be a family.

00:08:09.690 --> 00:08:12.210
I pray to God that he grant me
this one wish, this one wish

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:14.970
that I can hold my child
before I am shipped off.

00:08:20.370 --> 00:08:24.940
But I wasn't, I was shipped off
before I ever saw my beautiful

00:08:24.940 --> 00:08:26.910
baby Cecily [phonetic] born.

00:08:26.910 --> 00:08:33.120
I'd write in my journal
to keep my mind

00:08:33.120 --> 00:08:36.650
from picturing the horrors
of my perspective journey.

00:08:39.050 --> 00:08:41.510
When the dreaded day came, and
I had to tell Leah that I was,

00:08:41.510 --> 00:08:46.590
that I was shipping off,
she was broken hearted.

00:08:46.590 --> 00:08:50.550
We both were, we both realized
this might be the last time we

00:08:50.550 --> 00:08:53.970
would hear each other's voices.

00:08:58.130 --> 00:09:03.360
I pray that I would come
back to her but I fear

00:09:03.360 --> 00:09:05.660
that I may never see her again.

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:19.030
So, we were given three
sandwiches, a cup of coffee,

00:09:19.030 --> 00:09:27.190
a hundred rounds of ammunition
-- and off to France, we go!

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:37.580
[ Ship sounds ]

00:09:37.580 --> 00:09:41.940
We were packed like sardines
on this transport ships,

00:09:41.940 --> 00:09:44.780
these were one of the most
comfortable just whatsoever.

00:09:44.780 --> 00:09:49.810
No arrangements for bathing
was made, and the toilet

00:09:49.810 --> 00:09:54.090
to be overflowing with human
waste, I mean they'll be

00:09:54.090 --> 00:09:57.670
so filthy you would deny
yourself from ever using them.

00:09:57.670 --> 00:10:00.130
It's a lot of boys on this ship.

00:10:00.130 --> 00:10:02.030
So, you get the idea
it's pretty nasty stuff.

00:10:02.030 --> 00:10:10.490
I mean we don't catch [grunts]
from the filth and disease

00:10:10.490 --> 00:10:14.090
and the food, the food
wasn't much better either.

00:10:14.090 --> 00:10:15.990
For breakfast you'd get a
piece of unappetizing fish

00:10:15.990 --> 00:10:19.660
and for dinner a piece of meat
that was tough as leather.

00:10:19.660 --> 00:10:21.920
It would all be rejected
by everyone.

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:24.020
I mean the only edible
thing would be the pudding

00:10:24.020 --> 00:10:28.520
if you could keep it down
I mean, with a foul stench

00:10:28.520 --> 00:10:31.010
down below and the tossing
of ship above it was tough

00:10:31.010 --> 00:10:32.770
to keep anything down.

00:10:32.770 --> 00:10:37.060
I'd eat a few biscuits but
they'd always come back up.

00:10:37.060 --> 00:10:42.130
I walked to my bucket like
it was a natural thing.

00:10:42.130 --> 00:10:47.470
It's hard to believe but I
find myself missing the food

00:10:47.470 --> 00:10:49.770
from camp Upton.

00:10:54.380 --> 00:10:58.600
Up until now, I had
not realized the truth

00:10:58.600 --> 00:10:59.960
for the geography of the world.

00:10:59.960 --> 00:11:10.190
It is 2/3 water, it is
water, water, and water.

00:11:10.190 --> 00:11:16.180
I'd come though the rails and
I always dream of home, mamma,

00:11:16.180 --> 00:11:21.490
Leah, my soon to
be baby, dolphins,

00:11:21.490 --> 00:11:24.320
dolphins would follow our
ship for miles and always jump

00:11:24.320 --> 00:11:26.660
and play in the waves,
they all attract many

00:11:26.660 --> 00:11:29.040
of us boys to the rails.

00:11:29.040 --> 00:11:33.960
We'd all talk and, and
think about the death

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:37.920
that lay ahead for us.

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:45.890
Interesting days, days full
of spirit, full of adventure,

00:11:47.680 --> 00:11:52.510
this was our great adventure.

00:11:52.510 --> 00:12:02.420
[ Rail sounds ]

00:12:02.420 --> 00:12:06.900
On land, we traveled third-class
railway cars, we go from England

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:11.280
and all the way to France and
on the way we see children

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:15.510
and women, oh the
women, the English women,

00:12:15.510 --> 00:12:19.330
they had these red cheeks and
red noses, the boy would just go

00:12:19.330 --> 00:12:22.150
"wow" when they would
see them, they'd all wave

00:12:22.150 --> 00:12:25.410
from their backyards when we
road passed on the trains.

00:12:25.410 --> 00:12:28.130
And the food, the
food wasn't so bad.

00:12:28.130 --> 00:12:31.330
In France we get for breakfast,
we'd get canned sausage, bread,

00:12:31.330 --> 00:12:35.310
butter, jam and coffee,
lots and lots of coffee.

00:12:35.310 --> 00:12:43.900
You see, a soldier cannot
fight without coffee.

00:12:43.900 --> 00:12:46.200
Once we got to France --

00:12:51.290 --> 00:12:53.590
things changed for us.

00:12:59.040 --> 00:13:04.350
The first village we came
to was blown to bits,

00:13:04.350 --> 00:13:12.300
and then the next, and the next.

00:13:12.300 --> 00:13:16.220
Death and destruction grieved
your eyes, you could --

00:13:17.830 --> 00:13:24.220
hear, feel the roar from the
battle, [inaudible] lying,

00:13:24.220 --> 00:13:27.320
pawns and trains were
shattered and splintered.

00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:33.960
The earth, the earth
was filled with holes,

00:13:33.960 --> 00:13:39.300
15 feet deep, 25 feet wide.

00:13:39.300 --> 00:13:45.230
Monster pits made
by monster guns.

00:13:46.280 --> 00:13:47.830
Such a beautiful country wrapped

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:52.170
in so much death
and destruction.

00:13:53.610 --> 00:13:56.450
As you got closer to the line
you could feel the earth shiver

00:13:56.450 --> 00:14:01.970
-- beneath your feet.

00:14:06.560 --> 00:14:09.390
Flashes from the
sky, from the guns

00:14:09.390 --> 00:14:13.000
and slow rising a
[inaudible] signals and flares.

00:14:16.450 --> 00:14:20.870
It all looked like, like a 4th

00:14:20.870 --> 00:14:24.800
of July firework
celebration from back home.

00:14:27.400 --> 00:14:33.550
There is an example
of greatness in men,

00:14:33.550 --> 00:14:35.240
but it's all being
degraded by the use

00:14:35.240 --> 00:14:38.510
to which these machines
are being put to.

00:14:38.510 --> 00:14:42.560
[ Explosion ]

00:14:42.560 --> 00:14:45.930
Big guns pounding away at the
French towns, turning them

00:14:45.930 --> 00:14:48.210
into piles of rubble, you had

00:14:48.210 --> 00:14:50.510
to respect the French
people, I did.

00:14:50.510 --> 00:14:56.760
Especially the women,
they had so much courage.

00:14:56.760 --> 00:14:58.810
They would stood a
tremendous amount of shielding.

00:14:58.810 --> 00:15:06.780
I remember one French madame,
a small woman, she was walking

00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:11.100
on her bare feet with tears in
her eyes, she had her hands up

00:15:11.100 --> 00:15:20.060
and she was saying
"J'ai peur, j'ai peur,

00:15:20.060 --> 00:15:24.680
aidez-moi, j'ai peur".

00:15:28.570 --> 00:15:33.220
"I'm scared, I'm
scared, please help".

00:15:41.570 --> 00:15:45.000
In my opinion, the use of shell

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.570
in war is a cowardly
thing to do.

00:15:47.570 --> 00:15:49.610
I mean, you're cutting out
combat and it comes at you

00:15:49.610 --> 00:15:56.000
so fast, that all you
can do is wait for death.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:59.970
I'd be glad to fight
face to face.

00:16:14.340 --> 00:16:16.830
We were part of a
huge offensive;

00:16:16.830 --> 00:16:18.740
it was called The Muse
our Gun Offensive.

00:16:18.740 --> 00:16:21.830
Our goal was to drive up between
the Arland [phonetic] forest

00:16:21.830 --> 00:16:23.320
and the News [phonetic] river.

00:16:23.320 --> 00:16:25.580
You see General Purshins
[phonetic] idea was

00:16:25.580 --> 00:16:27.350
to cut the German supply lines

00:16:27.350 --> 00:16:30.100
and drive the Germans
out of France.

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:33.410
But the problem with the argon
force was that it was so thick,

00:16:33.410 --> 00:16:37.030
with trees, you couldn't see
more than 10 feet in front

00:16:37.030 --> 00:16:39.370
of you and it was
filled with frowny bushes

00:16:39.370 --> 00:16:42.940
that would slice right through
you when you felt on them.

00:16:42.940 --> 00:16:44.560
Up until that offensive,

00:16:44.560 --> 00:16:48.960
no one knew if the
American could fight,

00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:52.890
but after that offensive,

00:16:52.890 --> 00:17:00.640
the world learned how
tough the dull boys were.

00:17:00.640 --> 00:17:05.640
Right before our big push,
our brigade general major,

00:17:05.640 --> 00:17:07.850
they gathered us
around a French square,

00:17:07.850 --> 00:17:17.940
our general looks intently
into each man's eyes --

00:17:17.940 --> 00:17:25.260
Boys I know you're dreadfully
keen to get in the game,

00:17:25.260 --> 00:17:32.900
and you're all going to punch it
and you'll make America proud --

00:17:42.200 --> 00:17:47.160
So, there you have it,
the faith of England

00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:52.090
and France in our hands.

00:17:55.870 --> 00:18:04.650
I became scare from the first
time since arriving in France.

00:18:04.650 --> 00:18:07.000
What scared me the most was the
probability that I would have

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:10.510
to die in a trench on
my, on my wedding day.

00:18:10.510 --> 00:18:13.700
I was content that I would
have to die in this war

00:18:13.700 --> 00:18:15.840
but I didn't want
to die in a trench

00:18:15.840 --> 00:18:18.320
on my wedding anniversary.

00:18:18.320 --> 00:18:24.250
I prayed to God that he
would grant me this wish.

00:18:26.320 --> 00:18:34.840
I wrote mamma to buy a bouquet
of chrysanthemums for Leah.

00:18:34.840 --> 00:18:45.700
I may not be alive on that day
-- but I would want her to know

00:18:45.700 --> 00:18:52.070
that I thought of her on
our wedding anniversary.

00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:08.690
Over the days I became really
good at writing really small,

00:19:08.690 --> 00:19:10.480
and writing letters
to Leah and Momma.

00:19:10.480 --> 00:19:14.460
I was really good at
utilizing every inch

00:19:14.460 --> 00:19:16.760
of blank space in the letter.

00:19:18.100 --> 00:19:21.710
It's a small item to
crawl about but --

00:19:21.710 --> 00:19:26.810
paper, paper has a high value in
war, and if you can utilize it

00:19:26.810 --> 00:19:28.110
to the fullest you feel

00:19:28.110 --> 00:19:31.300
like you've done
something to be proud of.

00:19:33.290 --> 00:19:39.950
War has a way of teaching
men how to be proud

00:19:39.950 --> 00:19:42.250
of the smallest victories.

00:19:47.730 --> 00:19:51.850
Over the next couple of
months, our nights became cold

00:19:51.850 --> 00:19:56.640
and became the filthiest most
rats infested places you could

00:19:56.640 --> 00:19:58.940
ever imagine.

00:20:03.440 --> 00:20:11.230
We lived and fought in
the mud, I hated the mud.

00:20:11.230 --> 00:20:16.900
A lot of men died in the mud.

00:20:16.900 --> 00:20:20.220
We called our homes
hell on earth.

00:20:20.220 --> 00:20:24.440
"Rats", rats would crawl all
over your face when you tried

00:20:24.440 --> 00:20:28.980
to sleep, and millions of flies
would feast over the dead men

00:20:28.980 --> 00:20:31.840
in the open graves, and
the cooties [phonetic],

00:20:33.210 --> 00:20:35.860
the cooties were the
greatest little devils.

00:20:35.860 --> 00:20:38.450
I mean, everyone had
them, of all whole sizes

00:20:38.450 --> 00:20:41.310
and breeds big [inaudible]
white ones

00:20:41.310 --> 00:20:43.440
and they'd always
find a warm spot,

00:20:43.440 --> 00:20:45.530
as soon as you put your head
down they crawl down and up

00:20:45.530 --> 00:20:47.790
and around your neck
and enter your trousers.

00:20:47.790 --> 00:20:49.090
I mean to refrain

00:20:49.090 --> 00:20:52.390
from scratching them it would
require all the will power you

00:20:52.390 --> 00:20:57.280
can muster.

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:02.950
Over time I, I became shaky

00:21:02.950 --> 00:21:05.250
for the continual
thunder of the guns --

00:21:07.330 --> 00:21:12.970
It affected -- it
affected your nerves --

00:21:18.910 --> 00:21:21.210
It affected a lot of the men --

00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:29.670
When a shell would break, I
would hug the ground listening

00:21:29.670 --> 00:21:31.380
for fragments of the
hot [inaudible] of metal

00:21:31.380 --> 00:21:34.430
to strike upon the earth.

00:21:34.430 --> 00:21:38.530
I was right next to the
coronel whose life was safe,

00:21:38.530 --> 00:21:41.670
when a piece of shrapnel
came flying in.

00:21:41.670 --> 00:21:44.460
If it wasn't for him
having his hand to his face

00:21:44.460 --> 00:21:48.070
and eating a piece of bread,

00:21:48.070 --> 00:21:51.580
his head would have been
blown completely off.

00:21:54.750 --> 00:21:57.620
Luck, luck had a lot

00:21:57.620 --> 00:22:01.160
to do whether you
lived or died in war.

00:22:03.800 --> 00:22:11.900
It's what scared you the most,
the luck part, it scared me.

00:22:21.240 --> 00:22:27.140
The action started that day
when the lieutenant picked me

00:22:27.140 --> 00:22:32.790
as a runner, I -- my job
was to carry messages

00:22:32.790 --> 00:22:35.230
to and from commanders.

00:22:36.490 --> 00:22:38.090
You see they would
send six men out hoping

00:22:38.090 --> 00:22:40.480
that one would get through.

00:22:40.480 --> 00:22:45.210
It is the most deadly,
suicidal job you can have,

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:47.870
to run between enemy lines,
dodging machine guns fire,

00:22:47.870 --> 00:22:53.900
hoping you weren't running past
a German sniper [gun sounds],

00:22:53.900 --> 00:22:55.940
waiting to pick you off.

00:22:55.940 --> 00:23:04.620
A lot of brave men died as
runners, brave tired men,

00:23:04.620 --> 00:23:12.090
dying as -- as errand boys.

00:23:12.090 --> 00:23:13.390
But, you know what?

00:23:13.390 --> 00:23:15.590
I was glad.

00:23:15.590 --> 00:23:18.010
I was glad because
I never wanted

00:23:18.010 --> 00:23:20.700
to kill a man with a bayonet.

00:23:20.700 --> 00:23:25.140
The English, they loved the
bayonet, they talked to it

00:23:25.140 --> 00:23:33.850
with such charm and animation,
"You must love the bayonet!"

00:23:33.850 --> 00:23:36.810
I resented that such a killing
instrument could ever be used

00:23:36.810 --> 00:23:39.110
in war.

00:23:41.580 --> 00:23:43.880
As a runner --

00:23:47.040 --> 00:23:50.350
You zig zag through the forest,
you don't just go from point A

00:23:50.350 --> 00:23:54.820
to point B, you hide behind
a tree, [gun fire] you fall

00:23:54.820 --> 00:24:00.110
to the ground you use your
senses, you run to another tree,

00:24:00.110 --> 00:24:05.750
you look for a landmark, you
wait for a shell to explode,

00:24:05.750 --> 00:24:12.670
you run, you fall to the ground,
you run, you fall to the ground,

00:24:12.670 --> 00:24:16.250
you run, you hide behind a
bush behind a dead [inaudible],

00:24:16.250 --> 00:24:20.770
behind a dead soldier.

00:24:20.770 --> 00:24:24.540
You see in war we use
anything and everything

00:24:24.540 --> 00:24:29.510
if it means your survival, the
smell, the smell of death is all

00:24:29.510 --> 00:24:33.240
around you, dead men black
with decay buried [inaudible]

00:24:33.240 --> 00:24:38.150
with body parts sticking
out of the ground it is;

00:24:38.150 --> 00:24:41.750
it is the most fearful
thing in the dark.

00:24:41.750 --> 00:24:45.530
I hated to leave a man
like that, but you have to.

00:24:45.530 --> 00:24:50.490
You have to go on; you
find the courage to go on.

00:24:50.490 --> 00:24:52.540
Is like, I run up the hill, I
am at the mercy of the snipers

00:24:52.540 --> 00:24:57.110
and the shells vivid flashes
of fire, my ears ring,

00:24:57.110 --> 00:25:01.710
my heart stops beating as I --
as I run up the hill I think

00:25:01.710 --> 00:25:07.110
of home, mama, Leah,
baby Cecily.

00:25:07.110 --> 00:25:09.810
I say a prayer to the lord
to get me through this safely

00:25:09.810 --> 00:25:11.610
and suddenly, another
shell explosion.

00:25:11.610 --> 00:25:15.270
[ Screams ]

00:25:15.270 --> 00:25:19.300
I hug the earth and I flat.

00:25:20.410 --> 00:25:26.860
I want to go on, it is worse to
wait for death than to face it.

00:25:26.860 --> 00:25:35.210
I curse this shell, surprise
that I am, that I'm still alive.

00:25:35.210 --> 00:25:40.820
I get up, I run, I run like
that, not a soul to be seen,

00:25:40.820 --> 00:25:44.060
every house torn down piles
in the middle of the streets.

00:25:44.060 --> 00:25:46.300
I climb over wreckage,
more men rotting,

00:25:46.300 --> 00:25:50.600
and I see one man straight
down in front of ruin church,

00:25:50.600 --> 00:25:58.330
and I am, I am glad that
he is not rotting away

00:25:58.330 --> 00:26:01.970
in some trench or in the woods.

00:26:05.480 --> 00:26:09.070
Luck, not to the celeber
[phonetic] farmhouse

00:26:09.070 --> 00:26:11.660
as if I [inaudible],
I deliver my messages

00:26:11.660 --> 00:26:15.440
and my important papers and
he scolds me, and questions me

00:26:15.440 --> 00:26:18.270
for taking so long,
and he orders me

00:26:18.270 --> 00:26:21.510
to immediately return
back to the trenches.

00:26:21.510 --> 00:26:29.160
[ Whispers ]

00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:37.100
And dejected I, yes sir.

00:26:37.100 --> 00:26:44.020
I, I must run through the
death and destruction again,

00:26:44.020 --> 00:26:53.550
I must run, past the dead
men I see two more dead men,

00:26:53.550 --> 00:26:58.310
so awful sights face
black, eyes gone.

00:26:58.310 --> 00:27:02.130
I see another one hunched
over position by his gun,

00:27:02.130 --> 00:27:05.980
face is indistinguishable.

00:27:05.980 --> 00:27:13.860
Its sickens me to run past the
dead men frightened, I run,

00:27:13.860 --> 00:27:20.710
I run [runs sounds] through my
heart bursts, I cannot breathe,

00:27:20.710 --> 00:27:23.230
I run down the hill,
out of the woods

00:27:23.230 --> 00:27:25.720
and back to our, our trenches.

00:27:45.060 --> 00:27:54.560
It no longer, occurs to me,
to [inaudible] in battle,

00:27:54.560 --> 00:27:58.600
to some distant 4th
of July celebration.

00:28:02.630 --> 00:28:07.050
I am incensed, that so many of
our dead men lie in the streets

00:28:07.050 --> 00:28:09.070
of the villages near
us unburied.

00:28:09.070 --> 00:28:10.920
I want all of us to go down

00:28:10.920 --> 00:28:15.780
and have their bodies all
completely buried but,

00:28:18.490 --> 00:28:22.280
no volunteers from
any of the dugouts.

00:28:22.280 --> 00:28:25.110
I'm not [inaudible] the job any
more than the other boys do,

00:28:25.110 --> 00:28:29.310
but I feel out of
decency the men,

00:28:29.310 --> 00:28:36.150
the men must be given
a human burial.

00:28:37.910 --> 00:28:45.340
Me, Fern [phonetic] and
Summers, we chose to go,

00:28:45.340 --> 00:28:47.970
we want to feel human again.

00:28:54.160 --> 00:28:56.510
We see one lad with a big
gaping hole in his chest;

00:28:56.510 --> 00:28:58.970
six inches wide, it must
have killed him instantly.

00:29:05.100 --> 00:29:08.350
I had seen another one, he is
much more of a pitiful sight,

00:29:08.350 --> 00:29:11.970
he was burnt to a cinder.

00:29:15.420 --> 00:29:23.860
It hurts to look upon them the
dead men, but I, I spill myself

00:29:23.860 --> 00:29:29.900
and I perform what I
consider a human beauty.

00:29:37.910 --> 00:29:49.460
As we put the men in the graves,
it almost feels as if it,

00:29:49.460 --> 00:29:51.950
is a reward for them --

00:29:55.930 --> 00:30:00.180
Mentally I feel, I feel sick.

00:30:01.600 --> 00:30:08.280
I'm reminded you to write
a letter to, to Leah,

00:30:08.280 --> 00:30:13.860
for the simple satisfaction
that I could do it.

00:30:13.860 --> 00:30:16.810
I write, and I tell her how much
I love her, and I pray that her

00:30:16.810 --> 00:30:19.970
and our baby Cecily are well.

00:30:25.040 --> 00:30:30.960
All night long, I
see the dead men.

00:30:39.170 --> 00:30:41.790
Especially the man
who was burnt,

00:30:43.330 --> 00:30:48.230
I pondered the mystery
of life and dead.

00:30:49.350 --> 00:30:52.770
I just witnessed
the wonder of life

00:30:52.770 --> 00:30:55.900
in the helplessness of dead.

00:30:57.950 --> 00:31:01.140
Why do men do it?

00:31:01.140 --> 00:31:02.440
Why did they kill?

00:31:02.440 --> 00:31:04.740
Why do they destroy?

00:31:09.100 --> 00:31:14.200
The cost of it, the
futility of it.

00:31:14.200 --> 00:31:18.530
Why not end this war?

00:31:18.530 --> 00:31:21.510
Spear all the men and women, I
mean this war will never be won

00:31:21.510 --> 00:31:30.570
at the battlefield, I have no
courage to live, no will to --

00:31:35.150 --> 00:31:37.450
To fight, to go on --

00:31:42.470 --> 00:31:52.550
I hold on thinking
of Lea, baby Cecily.

00:31:55.700 --> 00:32:01.010
My eyes are bad for
all the tear gas.

00:32:01.010 --> 00:32:03.970
My throat is sore, my
lungs are congested --

00:32:09.040 --> 00:32:13.080
As I look around I see
a war pitiful sight,

00:32:13.080 --> 00:32:15.840
I see some of our boys and
French soldiers who are been

00:32:15.840 --> 00:32:18.950
in tear gas, they
are in great pain.

00:32:20.630 --> 00:32:22.960
Their eyes are red and
swollen, there coughing

00:32:22.960 --> 00:32:26.740
and vomiting in there.

00:32:26.740 --> 00:32:29.850
Heavily burns around
the arms and the legs.

00:32:31.810 --> 00:32:37.100
You see, you cannot
smell mustard gas;

00:32:37.100 --> 00:32:41.750
your nose becomes accustomed
to it from smelling it so much.

00:32:41.750 --> 00:32:50.120
It almost has a sweet aroma
to it, like onions or garlic,

00:32:50.120 --> 00:32:57.910
once you're expose red spots
begin to show upon your skin,

00:32:57.910 --> 00:33:07.110
and eventually you feel the
pain and the swelling in nose

00:33:07.110 --> 00:33:17.070
and in your lungs and you
die, no, no, you, you drown,

00:33:17.070 --> 00:33:19.790
you drown from all the
mucus in your lungs.

00:33:21.570 --> 00:33:23.870
It is a brutal weapon --

00:33:29.040 --> 00:33:31.080
If she only knew how foolishly
I risked my life today,

00:33:31.080 --> 00:33:33.380
she would most definitely cry.

00:33:36.320 --> 00:33:41.170
I think how unfair this
business of war is,

00:33:41.170 --> 00:33:43.970
especially to all the
mothers and wives back home.

00:33:50.930 --> 00:33:54.910
After dinner, our
captain tells us that,

00:33:54.910 --> 00:33:58.190
our [inaudible] will be sent
all over to the German lines,

00:33:58.190 --> 00:34:01.350
and that we would go
over the top to mop

00:34:01.350 --> 00:34:04.800
up after wards into
no man's land.

00:34:04.800 --> 00:34:08.320
We would wait for his whistle,
climb out of these trenches,

00:34:08.320 --> 00:34:11.790
tumble out, charge 30 yards
to the [inaudible] tangle man

00:34:11.790 --> 00:34:16.950
and zigzag towards our
enemy, hoping to scape there.

00:34:16.950 --> 00:34:21.090
I grow angry at this war and the
men who prolong it and decide

00:34:21.090 --> 00:34:22.820
of so much destruction.

00:34:22.820 --> 00:34:34.380
I wonder if I will ever be
given the chance to see home.

00:34:41.090 --> 00:34:49.320
You are given orders to wait,
which gives us time to wonder

00:34:49.320 --> 00:34:55.640
and shutter about what the
night has stored for us.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:05.510
In the dark I, I used my
pack for a, for a pillow.

00:35:06.860 --> 00:35:14.920
I sit, I wait, I
pray, and I think --

00:35:18.500 --> 00:35:20.800
Are we fit to fight?

00:35:29.170 --> 00:35:31.470
No.

00:35:39.280 --> 00:35:41.580
At 9:00p.m. --

00:35:46.040 --> 00:35:48.100
The door to hell is
open [gun explosion].

00:35:48.100 --> 00:35:53.650
I mean, every gun fired
for all it's worth,

00:35:53.650 --> 00:35:56.800
it is the most wicked
snap and crack to them.

00:35:56.800 --> 00:35:59.650
All of which makes it
necessary to shut when talking,

00:35:59.650 --> 00:36:02.820
the skies filled up with
red, white, green flares

00:36:02.820 --> 00:36:05.180
over the entire German lines.

00:36:05.180 --> 00:36:07.850
It is [inaudible] which
continuing to an instant flash,

00:36:07.850 --> 00:36:10.830
million twinkling stars
to show up for one second

00:36:10.830 --> 00:36:14.320
and appear another's, but
a second later they are

00:36:14.320 --> 00:36:16.490
like beautiful dancing lights.

00:36:16.490 --> 00:36:23.620
The lieutenant, he comes
tearing down the trench steeping

00:36:23.620 --> 00:36:28.410
over [inaudible], heads and
ankles, and then he shouts,

00:36:28.410 --> 00:36:32.070
"I need six more runners,
one for each company now".

00:36:32.070 --> 00:36:34.550
No volunteers from
any of the dugouts.

00:36:34.550 --> 00:36:38.880
I hide my face and then
I hear Greyri [phonetic]!

00:36:47.690 --> 00:36:50.200
He picks me again,
he picks his victims.

00:36:50.200 --> 00:37:00.570
I, god I, will never make it
home, he also picks Riley,

00:37:00.570 --> 00:37:05.120
Soliman [phonetic] and Thompson,
a small man, a good man,

00:37:05.120 --> 00:37:09.550
who is so scared of
all the shouting.

00:37:09.550 --> 00:37:14.720
That night we were all
scared, but then he tells us

00:37:14.720 --> 00:37:17.280
that is our mission to
find first battalion

00:37:17.280 --> 00:37:18.580
and that it is imperative

00:37:18.580 --> 00:37:22.300
that we stablish a
communication line.

00:37:22.300 --> 00:37:25.510
We will wait for his whistle --

00:37:25.510 --> 00:37:31.530
[ Clock and Whistle ]

00:37:31.530 --> 00:37:33.410
And then we tumble out,
and we go all over the top

00:37:33.410 --> 00:37:36.410
into the dark, thorny
bush into no man's land.

00:37:36.410 --> 00:37:39.740
It's sticky and dark, and we
are immediately lost [thunders].

00:37:39.740 --> 00:37:43.450
Riley and I shout and suddenly I
don't know where a machinegun is

00:37:43.450 --> 00:37:50.800
and opens up [gunshots],
and Thompson is shot

00:37:50.800 --> 00:37:54.450
in the head, by a machinegun.

00:37:54.450 --> 00:37:58.910
Good bald pallid Thompson I
was, this morning I was joking

00:37:58.910 --> 00:38:01.870
with him and now he is no more.

00:38:01.870 --> 00:38:05.150
A good man, a father
of two and a man

00:38:05.150 --> 00:38:06.660
who should have never
been in the army.

00:38:06.660 --> 00:38:09.230
I mourn his lost, the
lieutenant returns and scolds

00:38:09.230 --> 00:38:14.250
at us for not keeping up.

00:38:14.250 --> 00:38:15.930
I believe I can keep
up better than Riley,

00:38:15.930 --> 00:38:18.400
so I work my way forward,
stumbling my head,

00:38:18.400 --> 00:38:20.600
almost slicing my arms off

00:38:20.600 --> 00:38:22.920
against the wet wire
hidden in the brush.

00:38:22.920 --> 00:38:25.690
Stabbing my hands and my
face, we are to the best

00:38:25.690 --> 00:38:28.740
of my knowledge deep into no
man's land, at plain sight

00:38:28.740 --> 00:38:34.760
from plain Kaiser's snipers, the
paces its fast and I'm panting

00:38:34.760 --> 00:38:37.530
and lieutenant he just
questionably he stops getting

00:38:37.530 --> 00:38:40.410
yells at us, ¡catch up!

00:38:40.410 --> 00:38:43.190
Distressingly we saw a living
trenches narrowing wide,

00:38:43.190 --> 00:38:46.590
crashing into a brush
thirsty but we cannot rest,

00:38:46.590 --> 00:38:52.610
with all the machinegun there's
all around us, breathless,

00:38:52.610 --> 00:38:56.460
senseless with fear, lieutenant
draws out his revolver

00:38:56.460 --> 00:38:58.980
with a pale face and he
is a sight for an artist.

00:38:58.980 --> 00:39:02.470
We must hurry to the other side
of the hill before we are cut

00:39:02.470 --> 00:39:04.770
down by machinegun fire.

00:39:04.770 --> 00:39:06.890
The gun sound, the thunder,
the flares are lightning,

00:39:06.890 --> 00:39:10.120
and the rain is [explosion
sounds] and then suddenly,

00:39:10.120 --> 00:39:12.290
right in from of lieutenant
and Riley a shell explodes,

00:39:12.290 --> 00:39:14.810
and I literally watch
them [Explosion] --

00:39:23.330 --> 00:39:26.970
Disappear.

00:39:29.470 --> 00:39:33.110
&gt;&gt; Mrs. Lea Greenwall,
deeply regret to inform you

00:39:33.110 --> 00:39:34.800
that it is officially reported

00:39:34.800 --> 00:39:39.210
that private Erwin W. Greenwall
infantry was wounded in action,

00:39:39.210 --> 00:39:41.870
October 8th, degree
undetermined,

00:39:41.870 --> 00:39:45.120
further information
when received.

00:40:21.040 --> 00:40:24.120
Is October 22th.

00:40:24.120 --> 00:40:32.970
I've been in the hospital
for about two weeks.

00:40:39.370 --> 00:40:45.480
Food hasn't been so bad,
not so good, but not so bad.

00:40:46.910 --> 00:40:50.770
For breakfast, I get a
bowl of rice, applesauce,

00:40:50.770 --> 00:40:55.920
bread and coffee, lots
and lots and coffee.

00:40:55.920 --> 00:40:58.330
I can't get enough to coffee.

00:40:59.380 --> 00:41:01.930
Every few days I get cornmeal
mush with plenty of sugar

00:41:01.930 --> 00:41:04.440
and what seems to be real milk,

00:41:05.680 --> 00:41:15.650
some of the best milk I've
had in a long, long time.

00:41:15.650 --> 00:41:18.400
As I clear the windowpanes
to look

00:41:18.400 --> 00:41:24.910
out what strikes me is the
change in color in nature,

00:41:24.910 --> 00:41:35.950
what used to be green and
is now red, yellow and gold.

00:41:49.040 --> 00:41:51.340
But I noticed the most
because I don't --

00:41:56.330 --> 00:42:00.310
I don't hear the continual
thunder from the shells anymore.

00:42:05.040 --> 00:42:07.340
It is quiet.

00:42:08.790 --> 00:42:10.300
The sun screams upon my back

00:42:10.300 --> 00:42:12.800
and I can hear a [inaudible]
bell ringing outside.

00:42:12.800 --> 00:42:21.880
Every morning I listen
to it, it's such a,

00:42:21.880 --> 00:42:24.900
such a pleasant reminder
of home.

00:42:24.900 --> 00:42:33.250
Miss Johnson, my nurse, she
comes to clean my wound.

00:42:35.750 --> 00:42:42.470
She is a kind, plumped red-faced
girl from the Lemoyne, Iowa.

00:42:44.010 --> 00:42:47.700
As she removes my dressing
a stream of pause flows

00:42:47.700 --> 00:42:52.000
through my wound, I was
struck by a piece of scrap

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:54.990
from the shell that killed
the lieutenant and Riley.

00:42:57.830 --> 00:43:01.940
The doctor, a first
lieutenant, a young man.

00:43:01.940 --> 00:43:04.370
He is of the opinion
that there is piece

00:43:04.370 --> 00:43:05.950
of shrapnel still
lodging my wound

00:43:05.950 --> 00:43:07.620
that it must be fished out.

00:43:07.620 --> 00:43:13.970
He says, "Son, I need to
do a little fishing" --

00:43:19.050 --> 00:43:25.970
So, he turns me over my side and
says, "This is going to hurt".

00:43:32.750 --> 00:43:38.850
For ten minutes, with his
fingers he pokes into the back

00:43:38.850 --> 00:43:44.670
of my leg, Miss Johnson
she holds down my leg,

00:43:44.670 --> 00:43:50.080
but I can't keep very
still, every time he digs

00:43:50.080 --> 00:43:53.150
into the back of my leg.

00:43:53.150 --> 00:43:55.450
He touches a nerve

00:43:58.650 --> 00:44:01.180
I -- I clench my fists, I grit
my teeth, I breath heavily,

00:44:01.180 --> 00:44:06.910
anything to help me
withstand without screaming.

00:44:06.910 --> 00:44:10.880
This fishing and poking
goes of everyday I was

00:44:10.880 --> 00:44:14.140
in the hospital just
about until finally I say,

00:44:14.140 --> 00:44:19.870
"No that was enough of
your fishing and poking".

00:44:19.870 --> 00:44:25.110
The doctor gives me a
dirty look, dissatisfied

00:44:25.110 --> 00:44:32.270
with my resolve, he orders
Miss Johnson to banish my leg

00:44:32.270 --> 00:44:37.770
and that is the end of that.

00:44:46.180 --> 00:44:54.290
As I look around, instead
of strong straight men,

00:44:54.290 --> 00:44:57.360
I see cripples in
every direction.

00:45:00.370 --> 00:45:03.590
They are all beyond cure.

00:45:03.590 --> 00:45:07.780
I noticed a boy coming out of
the operation room with one leg,

00:45:07.780 --> 00:45:10.880
and he has tears on his
face and he is crying

00:45:10.880 --> 00:45:13.180
for the incredible pain.

00:45:14.520 --> 00:45:18.180
Seems another doctor performed
one of his delicate operations.

00:45:20.590 --> 00:45:25.500
I notice a girl face foil,
17, who later I found

00:45:25.500 --> 00:45:28.010
out enlisted when it was 15.

00:45:29.280 --> 00:45:36.370
He continually, he
continually cries for his mama.

00:45:37.760 --> 00:45:42.270
He's having a piece of
shrapnel removed from his spine,

00:45:42.270 --> 00:45:45.970
10 inches of his spine show
from the skull downwards.

00:45:50.040 --> 00:45:54.280
I see men with great
burns faces distorted,

00:45:56.400 --> 00:46:01.780
all of them with fig
creeping wounds in them --

00:46:12.150 --> 00:46:15.690
And deeply affected and sadden
by all the mothers and wives,

00:46:19.190 --> 00:46:22.600
who gave up so many great
boys for this cause.

00:46:27.140 --> 00:46:28.800
And all the mothers I heard
so many boys cry out to,

00:46:28.800 --> 00:46:31.950
dying in the trenches
and in no man's land.

00:46:40.040 --> 00:46:43.260
Deep feelings are
long of missing me.

00:46:43.260 --> 00:46:46.180
I'm longing for a letter
of from Leah or mama

00:46:46.180 --> 00:46:47.480
that I cannot suppress.

00:46:47.480 --> 00:46:56.410
I dream of home, of Leah coming
to visit me with my baby.

00:47:00.430 --> 00:47:02.960
They are delicious dreams.

00:47:04.930 --> 00:47:07.420
I have faith that in a
few days, I will be home,

00:47:07.420 --> 00:47:13.300
and I will be able to give
Leah and baby Cecily a kiss.

00:47:23.040 --> 00:47:30.060
On October 31st, the
war started to end.

00:47:30.060 --> 00:47:32.980
Turkey capitulates and agrees
to lay down all her arms

00:47:32.980 --> 00:47:36.540
and Austria, she
throws up her hands.

00:47:37.650 --> 00:47:44.240
And on November 4th, a
soldier comes running

00:47:44.240 --> 00:47:46.970
in with a newspaper
and he shouts

00:47:46.970 --> 00:47:50.110
for our silence, he
has our attention.

00:47:50.110 --> 00:47:57.330
There is an expected law
and then calls it, "boys,

00:47:57.330 --> 00:48:03.690
Germany has agreed to sign the
armistice with the allies".

00:48:03.690 --> 00:48:13.550
Three cheers and a yell that
could be heard all the way back

00:48:13.550 --> 00:48:18.180
to Paris [cheers], church
bells ring and the friends

00:48:18.180 --> 00:48:19.480
with all the joy with the news.

00:48:19.480 --> 00:48:28.210
Shorty, shorty gets on the
piano and he starts swinging

00:48:28.210 --> 00:48:33.250
from the [inaudible]
leading the cheering.

00:48:33.250 --> 00:48:36.960
I cheered standing
up in bed and Walter,

00:48:36.960 --> 00:48:39.050
Walter plays the stars
spangled banner [music],

00:48:39.050 --> 00:48:42.360
and all the boys, they
gather around the piano.

00:48:42.360 --> 00:48:46.050
There is singing and
shouting, and dancing,

00:48:46.050 --> 00:48:49.940
and drinking, plenty
of drinking.

00:48:49.940 --> 00:48:53.360
I wasn't a drinking man but
that day I had a few drinks,

00:48:53.360 --> 00:48:57.760
and as I look out the window,
I remember thinking how glad

00:48:57.760 --> 00:49:02.510
that I was alive and that this
war, this war is finally over.

00:49:02.510 --> 00:49:11.180
[ Music ]

00:49:11.180 --> 00:49:25.950
A week later, Monday, November
11th, 1918, the armistice

00:49:25.950 --> 00:49:29.920
with Germany is signed, all
terms are agreed upon it,

00:49:29.920 --> 00:49:32.880
all fires ceases at 11 o'clock.

00:49:32.880 --> 00:49:37.060
And my first thoughts are for
the lads, no doubt many who gave

00:49:37.060 --> 00:49:40.970
up their life's right
before 11 o'clock.

00:49:47.670 --> 00:49:49.970
It is a pity.

00:49:52.520 --> 00:49:55.120
On our transport ships we,

00:49:55.120 --> 00:49:58.420
we steam into the
harbor of Newport News.

00:50:00.750 --> 00:50:05.390
Landlines, twinkling like mirror
stars and I can see the flashes

00:50:05.390 --> 00:50:10.510
from Tralee wires, all evidence
that we are in good old America.

00:50:10.510 --> 00:50:15.590
I don't think of America
as much as I think

00:50:15.590 --> 00:50:21.080
of Leah and baby Cecily.

00:50:21.080 --> 00:50:30.520
On our ships I get my things,
I make my bed, I tight my bunk,

00:50:30.520 --> 00:50:42.260
I dress, I shine my shoes,
I shave with infinite care.

00:50:42.260 --> 00:50:45.720
At 9:30 I'm given my pass,

00:50:45.720 --> 00:50:53.330
I am ready to go
[inaudible], I walk on air.

00:50:54.800 --> 00:50:57.100
The doctor, he comes
on board and he --

00:51:04.620 --> 00:51:11.570
Checks my wound,
no pus, no pain.

00:51:11.570 --> 00:51:13.580
I make it down to the
doctor without assistance

00:51:13.580 --> 00:51:15.610
and I see the ever-present
Red Cross ladies

00:51:15.610 --> 00:51:19.510
with chocolate and cigarettes.

00:51:21.190 --> 00:51:24.310
I will never forget the
bravery and kindness

00:51:24.310 --> 00:51:28.550
of the women of the Red Cross.

00:51:29.660 --> 00:51:35.000
I see advertising signs, and
wooden houses and civilians,

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:38.710
all of which are a
sight so familiar to me

00:51:38.710 --> 00:51:44.110
and glad it's my heart, I sing
and I whistle all the way home.

00:51:46.340 --> 00:51:51.760
When we get to camp Stewart,
I am reminded of what I said

00:51:51.760 --> 00:51:53.840
when I left camp Upton

00:51:53.840 --> 00:51:59.690
that I hope I never
see the bears again,

00:51:59.690 --> 00:52:04.190
but how glad I am
to see them now.

00:52:04.190 --> 00:52:07.930
I am home --

00:52:12.040 --> 00:52:13.910
I know it; I can feel
it in every thought

00:52:13.910 --> 00:52:15.490
in every bone in my body.

00:52:15.490 --> 00:52:20.970
I cannot believe
my good fortune.

00:52:32.140 --> 00:52:34.440
I am finally going home.

