00:55:22.120 --> 00:55:25.010
to honor, to celebrate
the centennial

00:55:25.010 --> 00:55:28.180
of the first World War,
and at first I was very,

00:55:28.180 --> 00:55:32.180
as I've said it many times,
in couple interviews --

00:55:32.180 --> 00:55:38.060
the work that someone did
is so valuable because a lot

00:55:38.060 --> 00:55:39.620
of the diaries, all
the other diaries,

00:55:39.620 --> 00:55:42.340
they weren't transcribed
so they were written.

00:55:42.340 --> 00:55:45.090
So, by her tight writing it

00:55:45.090 --> 00:55:49.480
and then being digitized it
allowed me to basically treat it

00:55:49.480 --> 00:55:52.480
as a text and I can basically
read it and take notes from it.

00:55:52.480 --> 00:55:57.030
And so, from that process I just
basically created to the stuff

00:55:57.030 --> 00:55:59.950
that I really like and try to
creating a begin, middle and end

00:55:59.950 --> 00:56:02.610
with my director, Patrick Lewis,

00:56:02.610 --> 00:56:04.960
he should be here
somewhere, their he is.

00:56:04.960 --> 00:56:11.110
And so, that's how, that's
how we kind of, we came to it.

00:56:11.110 --> 00:56:17.010
But I mean, it was a very
tedious long process still,

00:56:17.010 --> 00:56:21.920
it took me six months, the goal
was always to, do I need it now?

00:56:21.920 --> 00:56:23.220
[Laughter].

00:56:23.220 --> 00:56:28.540
I didn't need it
there, I hate mics.

00:56:28.540 --> 00:56:32.710
So, yes, I basically what I
would do is I would highlight

00:56:32.710 --> 00:56:34.530
stuff that I like and I
would put it into a document

00:56:34.530 --> 00:56:37.690
and then I would read through
that, and I read the diaries

00:56:37.690 --> 00:56:39.200
from beginning to end.

00:56:39.200 --> 00:56:43.500
So, and then eventually I go
from 30.000 words, 15.000 words,

00:56:43.500 --> 00:56:47.100
10.000 words, and I finally had
needed to get it to 7.000 words.

00:56:47.100 --> 00:56:49.900
And then I started crafting
it into what it is today.

00:56:49.900 --> 00:56:53.080
But the diary is so powerful,
he was such an eloquent writing,

00:56:53.080 --> 00:56:58.190
I mean, you could make four
plays out of his diary.

00:56:58.190 --> 00:57:01.080
So, it was really tough, because
if anybody knows anything

00:57:01.080 --> 00:57:04.190
about editing or writing,
deletion is the toughest thing

00:57:04.190 --> 00:57:10.700
to do, because I did his passage
on the ship was about as crucial

00:57:10.700 --> 00:57:13.720
as his time on the
trenches and he really talks

00:57:13.720 --> 00:57:16.360
about it really elaborately,
but you know,

00:57:16.360 --> 00:57:21.570
in fairness to theatrical
production we had

00:57:21.570 --> 00:57:25.530
to move past that so, yes.

00:57:30.330 --> 00:57:31.670
&gt;&gt; What do you regret
the most leaving out?

00:57:31.670 --> 00:57:34.550
If you had another 30
minutes, what would you put in?

00:57:34.550 --> 00:57:36.480
&gt;&gt; Douglas Taurel:
That's a great question.

00:57:36.480 --> 00:57:40.890
The very beginning
because there was a couple,

00:57:40.890 --> 00:57:45.150
two moments that I couldn't find
a way, because I was restrained

00:57:45.150 --> 00:57:49.200
by time, she said "you have
45 to 50 minutes only",

00:57:49.200 --> 00:57:52.050
so that was a big parameter
for what I had to do.

00:57:52.050 --> 00:57:53.950
But there was a moment in
the diary in the beginning

00:57:53.950 --> 00:57:56.890
where he really doesn't
want to go off to war,

00:57:56.890 --> 00:58:02.120
and he actually gets on a train
and he is going to go AWOL,

00:58:02.120 --> 00:58:05.750
and he was a man apparently,
for what I deduced,

00:58:05.750 --> 00:58:07.470
his name was everything
to him --

00:58:07.470 --> 00:58:11.040
and so he was terrified that
Leah, he loved his wife so much,

00:58:11.040 --> 00:58:14.840
that Leah would be stained
with having a name of a husband

00:58:14.840 --> 00:58:16.140
who would had gone AWOL.

00:58:16.140 --> 00:58:18.110
So, he literally
gets on the train

00:58:18.110 --> 00:58:22.170
and he jumps off last minute,
and he talks about it, and how,

00:58:22.170 --> 00:58:25.190
the steam the engine,
is something right

00:58:25.190 --> 00:58:26.970
out of Harry Potter the
way he describes it.

00:58:26.970 --> 00:58:30.520
And it's beautiful, and I had
it in there, but it didn't,

00:58:30.520 --> 00:58:33.920
it just, it didn't fit with the
act that I was trying to do,

00:58:33.920 --> 00:58:35.220
what we were trying to do.

00:58:35.220 --> 00:58:39.040
And so, the other point,
when he's in the trenches,

00:58:39.040 --> 00:58:43.190
he is actually told he can
go home, and he is static

00:58:43.190 --> 00:58:44.730
and then they come
up to him and say,

00:58:44.730 --> 00:58:48.760
"I'm sorry we made a mistake, it
is not you it is someone else".

00:58:48.760 --> 00:58:51.440
And so, he is just like
that's where that line comes

00:58:51.440 --> 00:58:54.260
"I have no will to live, I have
no courage to fight anymore".

00:58:54.260 --> 00:58:55.700
So, I took that line
and I put it there

00:58:55.700 --> 00:58:57.250
because he is really
devastated from that,

00:58:57.250 --> 00:58:58.550
and that's when he says,

00:58:58.550 --> 00:59:00.140
"I think I will never
make it home now".

00:59:00.140 --> 00:59:02.500
And he was part the
last battalion,

00:59:02.500 --> 00:59:05.850
if anybody knows anything
about the last battalion is,

00:59:05.850 --> 00:59:10.640
they suffered tremendous
casualties, and from what I get

00:59:10.640 --> 00:59:13.380
from Greeny, that's
how I call him

00:59:13.380 --> 00:59:15.610
because that's how the boys
call him they call him Greeny.

00:59:15.610 --> 00:59:21.750
He was a fairly successful
man, and he had a good shop,

00:59:21.750 --> 00:59:23.730
you know, he had a
wife who had a bay,

00:59:23.730 --> 00:59:26.760
he had a good life he sound
like he was very educated,

00:59:26.760 --> 00:59:30.240
he would have to be
to write like this.

00:59:30.240 --> 00:59:35.970
And so, to see him part of
the trenches, living with rats

00:59:35.970 --> 00:59:39.120
and there were parts were
they were starving to death,

00:59:39.120 --> 00:59:41.030
they had no water
they had a choice

00:59:41.030 --> 00:59:45.130
to drinking chlorinated
water or no water.

00:59:45.130 --> 00:59:48.640
To see him go from that extreme
to that extreme, and then,

00:59:48.640 --> 00:59:50.980
and the whole time all he
does is to talk about Lea

00:59:50.980 --> 00:59:54.990
and baby Cecily, so he
must have been madly,

00:59:54.990 --> 00:59:56.540
would they be madly in love?

00:59:56.540 --> 00:59:58.510
I had to ask because --

00:59:58.510 --> 01:00:02.040
[ Background voice ]

01:00:02.040 --> 01:00:03.450
Because it feels like, I mean,

01:00:03.450 --> 01:00:05.960
almost every paragraph
he mentions her name,

01:00:05.960 --> 01:00:09.020
so those are the two big spots

01:00:09.020 --> 01:00:12.310
that I wish I could have
somehow crafted, you know.

01:00:12.310 --> 01:00:14.430
It seemed like he wants to go
home so bad that he even gets

01:00:14.430 --> 01:00:17.460
into a train he's willing to
go AWOL, but he gets scared

01:00:17.460 --> 01:00:19.500
because he's afraid of what
that will do to his name

01:00:19.500 --> 01:00:22.970
and he jumps the train, so yes.

01:00:29.110 --> 01:00:30.410
Ask her.

