ripple, which means there's

01:20:35.450 --> 01:20:38.330
about 34 to 36 of us with our
company command in the middle,

01:20:38.330 --> 01:20:40.770
and they're called by the
ripple because they go one

01:20:40.770 --> 01:20:44.260
after another, sort of
like a, like dominoes.

01:20:44.260 --> 01:20:45.770
And if anyone makes a mistake

01:20:45.770 --> 01:20:49.560
in the exact way how you're
told how to do these exercises,

01:20:49.560 --> 01:20:51.240
you have to start all
over the beginning.

01:20:51.240 --> 01:21:01.330
And Adam Smith a southern back
Missouri kid, a really nice guy

01:21:02.510 --> 01:21:08.940
but he wasn't a good soldier,
he made a mistake and we had

01:21:08.940 --> 01:21:10.970
to start all over the beginning.

01:21:10.970 --> 01:21:17.250
So, my company commander
comes up and he starts yelling

01:21:17.250 --> 01:21:20.430
"Is anybody here
angry at recruit Smith

01:21:20.430 --> 01:21:21.730
for making a mistake?"

01:21:21.730 --> 01:21:25.740
So, I speak up "yes sir, I am
angry at recruit Smith sir,

01:21:25.740 --> 01:21:28.740
I fell we all shouldn't
start at the beginning

01:21:28.740 --> 01:21:33.010
because of recruit Smith sir!"

01:21:33.010 --> 01:21:37.660
Well that was a life longing
lesson because I, and only I had

01:21:37.660 --> 01:21:39.690
to do all the exercises.

01:21:39.690 --> 01:21:44.070
I had to go to each recruit,
state my name, do the exercises

01:21:44.070 --> 01:21:48.790
and then ask them if I
had done them correctly.

01:21:48.790 --> 01:21:50.110
"My name is recruit Williams

01:21:50.110 --> 01:21:53.510
and I will be doing
exercises for you".

01:21:53.510 --> 01:22:03.760
[ Background sounds ]

01:22:03.760 --> 01:22:05.160
"Did I do my exercises
correctly?

01:22:05.160 --> 01:22:06.520
My name is recruit Williams

01:22:06.520 --> 01:22:08.510
and I will be doing
exercises for you".

01:22:08.510 --> 01:22:21.270
[ Background sounds ]

01:22:21.270 --> 01:22:22.570
"Did I do my exercises
correctly?

01:22:22.570 --> 01:22:24.400
My name is recruit Williams

01:22:24.400 --> 01:22:26.510
and I will be doing
exercises for you".

01:22:26.510 --> 01:22:38.680
[ Background sounds ]

01:22:38.680 --> 01:22:43.790
"Did I do my exercises
correctly?"

01:22:43.790 --> 01:22:48.500
Needless to say, it was
humbling to say the least.

01:22:48.500 --> 01:22:51.390
So, my company commander
comes up and starts yelling

01:22:51.390 --> 01:22:55.470
"are you still angry at recruit
Smith for making a mistake?"

01:22:55.470 --> 01:23:04.080
--

01:23:04.080 --> 01:23:08.170
And at that minute a
light bulb went off,

01:23:08.170 --> 01:23:16.900
I just realized what this was,
this was a game, life is a game,

01:23:16.900 --> 01:23:20.190
you have to play
the game with rules,

01:23:20.190 --> 01:23:24.560
we're all in this together, and
no man is above another man,

01:23:24.560 --> 01:23:28.330
and the way you survive is
by helping your fellow man

01:23:28.330 --> 01:23:30.890
and working together as a team.

01:23:30.890 --> 01:23:39.510
Is the way you survive war and
it's the way you survive life.

01:23:39.510 --> 01:24:15.040
[ Music ]

01:24:15.040 --> 01:24:17.340
I'm tired of being scared.

01:24:19.730 --> 01:24:22.440
I just want to come home and
no matter how hard I try,

01:24:22.440 --> 01:24:24.970
I can't seem to come home.

01:24:32.050 --> 01:24:35.660
When it goes off to war,

01:24:35.660 --> 01:24:37.400
you just don't come back
the same person you were

01:24:37.400 --> 01:24:44.620
as you left, you just don't
sit at the dinner table

01:24:44.620 --> 01:24:46.220
and say [inaudible] now.

01:24:46.220 --> 01:24:48.960
It just doesn't work that way.

01:24:48.960 --> 01:24:53.740
The adjustment is
tough, it's real tough.

01:24:53.740 --> 01:24:59.530
I have an incredible temper
now, one I never had before.

01:24:59.530 --> 01:25:06.820
I'm abusive to my
wife, can't hold a job,

01:25:06.820 --> 01:25:08.120
nothing matters to me anymore.

01:25:08.120 --> 01:25:15.180
And the worst part of being
back home is I don't want

01:25:17.970 --> 01:25:25.390
to touch my son, I'm terrified
of infecting him with the evil

01:25:25.390 --> 01:25:28.140
that I've seen and done.

01:25:28.140 --> 01:25:30.990
To grab my boy with the
same bloody hands, I feel,

01:25:30.990 --> 01:25:34.970
as I would destroy his
purity, I would infect him.

01:25:39.830 --> 01:25:46.440
When you go off to war
you goes off as a kid,

01:25:46.440 --> 01:25:54.460
but when you come back is all,
is dirty inside, is all-hollow.

01:25:54.460 --> 01:25:58.160
I was in the first
lining face at Inujima.

01:25:58.160 --> 01:26:04.550
I, I saw hundreds of dead men,
faces gone, bodies exposed,

01:26:04.550 --> 01:26:07.820
that's what Inujima was,
it was a killing field.

01:26:07.820 --> 01:26:10.470
I mean, when we landed
and we took a hell

01:26:10.470 --> 01:26:12.080
of a [inaudible] they
met us with everything.

01:26:12.080 --> 01:26:14.380
I remember just running on
the beach and cover my head

01:26:14.380 --> 01:26:16.630
and crying like a baby
when my knees were shaking,

01:26:16.630 --> 01:26:18.720
my body was trembling
like it was,

01:26:18.720 --> 01:26:21.510
like it was, like it was jelly.

01:26:21.510 --> 01:26:29.020
When we were on the beach, my
captain comes up and he yells,

01:26:29.020 --> 01:26:34.320
"I need three guys to go with me
to see what the jets are up to!"

01:26:34.320 --> 01:26:37.560
I thought anything is better
than being stuck here.

01:26:37.560 --> 01:26:43.930
So, me, Vincent and Lucky we
volunteered, we walked over,

01:26:43.930 --> 01:26:46.560
over the rocks into
the dark jungle.

01:26:52.040 --> 01:26:53.340
It was silent.

01:26:53.340 --> 01:26:57.580
It was as if you walk through
the front door or something told

01:26:57.580 --> 01:27:03.450
who didn't want you to be there.

01:27:03.450 --> 01:27:06.160
After several hours,
we realize we was lost.

01:27:06.160 --> 01:27:08.840
"Hey man, where the
fuck are we?"

01:27:08.840 --> 01:27:14.090
At that moment my captain
was shot, and I spot the jap

01:27:14.090 --> 01:27:17.900
who shot him, so I bring my
rifle and I bring him down,

01:27:17.900 --> 01:27:21.370
and Lucky yells "make
sure he's dead, do it!".

01:27:21.370 --> 01:27:25.270
So, I run up to him and
I see him still moving

01:27:25.270 --> 01:27:27.510
so I bring up my knife and --

01:27:27.510 --> 01:27:42.050
[ Whispers and screams ]

01:27:42.050 --> 01:27:48.780
I just slit a man's throat.

01:27:48.780 --> 01:27:50.640
No matter what the
army train me to do

01:27:50.640 --> 01:27:52.080
but they can never
train me to what it's

01:27:52.080 --> 01:27:57.940
like to kill another human
being, and I, and I just did,

01:27:57.940 --> 01:28:01.740
and I felt terrible
because of it.

01:28:01.740 --> 01:28:06.750
I walked away, I looked at
my hand, and it was covered

01:28:06.750 --> 01:28:09.730
in blood, as if someone
spilled a red gallon

01:28:09.730 --> 01:28:11.030
of red paint all over me.

01:28:11.030 --> 01:28:15.690
When it goes off to war
you don't kill someone

01:28:15.690 --> 01:28:20.350
in the kind way, you
do it with cruelty.

01:28:20.350 --> 01:28:27.920
You're scared, you kill and if
you don't kill you get killed.

01:28:32.040 --> 01:28:34.850
War is nasty, is terrible.

01:28:34.850 --> 01:28:38.380
There are few things
you did or endured

01:28:38.380 --> 01:28:40.280
in combat ever leave you,

01:28:40.280 --> 01:28:42.540
the thought of this events
there is vivid in my mind

01:28:42.540 --> 01:28:47.560
as I was, as I was in combat.

01:28:50.120 --> 01:28:53.680
Physical wounds generally
heal in time.

01:28:57.110 --> 01:29:05.950
But the memories of battle
they, they cut to deep they

01:29:11.070 --> 01:29:18.260
They burn your soul, they
never go away, no, never.

01:29:18.260 --> 01:29:32.580
I was a nice kid before I left,
and now I'm not, I'm broken.

01:29:39.550 --> 01:29:44.180
I've become good friends with
Jim and Jack you may know

01:29:44.180 --> 01:29:48.090
as Jim Beam and Jack Daniels.

01:29:48.090 --> 01:29:50.510
They help me forget.

01:29:50.510 --> 01:30:29.040
[ Helicopter ]

01:30:29.040 --> 01:30:38.510
Greeny, you are working too
hard man, what are you doing?

01:30:38.510 --> 01:30:42.470
Search and destroy,
digging holes.

01:30:42.470 --> 01:30:45.550
Greeny it ain't matter what you
do man the [inaudible] could be

01:30:45.550 --> 01:30:48.620
right in front of you and
you still wouldn't know it.

01:30:48.620 --> 01:30:51.810
They're so better on these hills
doesn't matter how many holes

01:30:51.810 --> 01:30:54.470
you dig or [inaudible]
bombs you drop on them,

01:30:54.470 --> 01:30:56.940
we ain't never going
to get them out.

01:30:56.940 --> 01:30:58.820
So, stop digging that
hole man and come

01:30:58.820 --> 01:31:00.250
over here and smoke some shit.

01:31:00.250 --> 01:31:02.620
You got to take it easy now man,

01:31:02.620 --> 01:31:06.840
or else you ain't
going to make it.

01:31:06.840 --> 01:31:10.790
Ain't no cowards at this
place, just the life

01:31:10.790 --> 01:31:13.970
or dead, here, smoke some.

01:31:17.590 --> 01:31:19.510
You don't smoke?

01:31:19.510 --> 01:31:24.230
[ Laughter ]

01:31:24.230 --> 01:31:28.280
You will, give yourself a
week and you'll be smoking,

01:31:28.280 --> 01:31:30.320
you got to smoke to
escape the beast,

01:31:30.320 --> 01:31:32.660
escape hell, escape reality.

01:31:32.660 --> 01:31:37.910
Doesn't matter how much
training you've done,

01:31:37.910 --> 01:31:40.900
Vietnam is a whole new
fucked up world man,

01:31:40.900 --> 01:31:48.000
this place is a steam bag, 24/7
infested with bugs and insects

01:31:48.000 --> 01:31:49.860
and snakes, and I
hate snakes man.

01:31:49.860 --> 01:31:52.920
They got the most
poisonous snake

01:31:52.920 --> 01:31:56.540
in the world here the two step.

01:31:56.540 --> 01:31:58.470
And you know why it's
called the two-step.

01:31:58.470 --> 01:32:00.070
Because if that son
of a bitch bites you,

01:32:00.070 --> 01:32:01.870
you get two steps
before you die.

01:32:01.870 --> 01:32:05.040
[ Laughter ]

01:32:05.040 --> 01:32:09.670
Oh shit! Green, there's a
two-step right next to you,

01:32:09.670 --> 01:32:13.750
no I ain't messing
around is right there.

01:32:13.750 --> 01:32:18.970
I'm just going to
reach over there

01:32:18.970 --> 01:32:22.780
and get my knife,
don't move man.

01:32:22.780 --> 01:32:26.270
I'm just messing around, I'm
just messing with you baby,

01:32:26.270 --> 01:32:32.420
take it easy man
here man smoke some.

01:32:32.420 --> 01:32:35.240
Aww damn, you reading?

01:32:35.240 --> 01:32:38.280
Now, where are you from?

01:32:38.280 --> 01:32:41.950
Iowa? Man, you are
far from home,

01:32:41.950 --> 01:32:44.410
this place ain't
nothing like Iowa man.

01:32:44.410 --> 01:32:46.000
Tell me something man,

01:32:46.000 --> 01:32:48.440
what's everyone saying
about us back home?

01:32:48.440 --> 01:32:50.540
Because I keep reading in my
dad's letter that he's starting

01:32:50.540 --> 01:32:52.640
to have doubts about
us and this war,

01:32:52.640 --> 01:32:56.110
says we shouldn't be over here.

01:32:56.110 --> 01:32:58.370
There's people back home
marching and protesting

01:32:58.370 --> 01:33:00.030
against us calling
us baby killers.

01:33:00.030 --> 01:33:03.470
I ain't a baby killer
man, these sons of bitches

01:33:03.470 --> 01:33:04.960
up in the hills ain't no babies,

01:33:04.960 --> 01:33:07.390
if they are they're some badass
motherfucking babies firing 8mm

01:33:07.390 --> 01:33:10.570
machine guns at us.

01:33:10.570 --> 01:33:14.430
Yes, if everyone from
back home were with us

01:33:14.430 --> 01:33:16.330
when we were stranded and
surrounded by four battalions

01:33:16.330 --> 01:33:19.920
of NDAs they'd thought
different about us in this war.

01:33:19.920 --> 01:33:23.860
Pinned own taking fire
from every direction.

01:33:23.860 --> 01:33:26.830
Chasing around flying
through the air,

01:33:26.830 --> 01:33:28.670
buddies being blown away.

01:33:28.670 --> 01:33:32.860
See, that's the shit
about war Greeny,

01:33:32.860 --> 01:33:40.160
that no one prepares you
for, it's the sound of war,

01:33:40.160 --> 01:33:45.020
bullets cracking, bombs landing,
[inaudible] of shells exploding,

01:33:45.020 --> 01:33:48.690
men screaming and
yelling for their mommas.

01:33:48.690 --> 01:33:53.930
It's just a big ball of deity
noise man and when you hear

01:33:53.930 --> 01:33:56.280
that shit, that's when you
know the beast is hungry man

01:33:56.280 --> 01:34:00.210
and that's why you smoke
man, to escape the beast!

01:34:00.210 --> 01:34:10.050
Every time I get high
man I get closer to home,

01:34:10.050 --> 01:34:11.810
and see myself walking
through the back door

01:34:11.810 --> 01:34:16.210
and hear my mama go "dinner's
almost ready baby" sit

01:34:16.210 --> 01:34:20.780
on the back porsche and watching
these Texas sunsets it'll

01:34:22.610 --> 01:34:23.910
be quiet.

01:34:23.910 --> 01:34:28.230
When I get out of
here I don't want

01:34:28.230 --> 01:34:31.440
to hear another thing
about Vietnam or war.

01:34:31.440 --> 01:34:35.450
What's that?

01:34:35.450 --> 01:34:36.750
You want a hit?

01:34:36.750 --> 01:34:43.510
Yes, I thought you'd
come around.

01:34:43.510 --> 01:35:15.320
[ Music ]

01:35:15.320 --> 01:35:17.380
I've been back from Iraq
for about a year now

01:35:17.380 --> 01:35:19.190
and I already want to go back.

01:35:19.190 --> 01:35:22.140
I miss the edge baby, yes.

01:35:22.140 --> 01:35:26.190
I miss that, I miss the feeling
of 50-caliber machine gun,

01:35:26.190 --> 01:35:28.680
the feeling of the power
coursing through your veins

01:35:28.680 --> 01:35:30.890
with the pull of a trigger,
the sounds of locking

01:35:30.890 --> 01:35:35.480
and loading your guns,
[shoots] get some!

01:35:35.480 --> 01:35:39.100
Man, I miss that.

01:35:39.100 --> 01:35:46.650
But what I miss the most, I
miss my buddies, my brothers.

01:35:46.650 --> 01:35:47.950
But it's crazy because I know

01:35:47.950 --> 01:35:50.250
that once I go back
I'd be all depressed.

01:35:53.040 --> 01:35:56.830
I wish I could feel more
comfortable being back home,

01:35:56.830 --> 01:36:02.450
my wife she doesn't, she
doesn't want me to come back,

01:36:02.450 --> 01:36:03.750
and I don't blame her.

01:36:03.750 --> 01:36:05.050
But I've only done
one deployment,

01:36:05.050 --> 01:36:06.620
some of my buddies have
done two, three, four,

01:36:06.620 --> 01:36:09.010
five deployments they've been
back to back to back to back!

01:36:09.010 --> 01:36:11.360
Some of their crappie
experiences are

01:36:11.360 --> 01:36:13.660
so freaking overwhelming.

01:36:18.150 --> 01:36:19.450
So, I've been back home,

01:36:19.450 --> 01:36:22.500
I've been reminded how
much I miss my wife.

01:36:24.370 --> 01:36:27.230
I do, I love her.

01:36:27.230 --> 01:36:28.800
When you're over there you
miss the feel of a women,

01:36:28.800 --> 01:36:32.660
you miss the smell of
a women, but I'm having

01:36:32.660 --> 01:36:36.270
such a hard time finding
things to talking her about,

01:36:36.270 --> 01:36:41.880
I mean it's not her fault it's
just a lot of things she says

01:36:41.880 --> 01:36:54.400
to me it's so meaningless and
senseless "honey should we go

01:36:54.400 --> 01:37:03.470
to Kids Sauce for dinner or
should we go to the movies?

01:37:03.470 --> 01:37:10.500
But I think what we really
need to do is paint the kitchen

01:37:10.500 --> 01:37:11.840
and get some brand new frapes,

01:37:11.840 --> 01:37:16.120
what we really need is
a brand-new crock pot".

01:37:16.120 --> 01:37:22.550
What do I care about a crockpot?

01:37:22.550 --> 01:37:29.640
I mean I don't tell her that
but that's what I'm thinking,

01:37:29.640 --> 01:37:37.780
how can I talk about this
mundane crap when I've been

01:37:37.780 --> 01:37:45.430
over there blowing crap away
like a freaking videogame.

01:37:45.430 --> 01:37:48.800
Everyone back here they don't
have to sing appreciation

01:37:48.800 --> 01:37:53.900
for being alive as you do
because it ain't life or death,

01:37:53.900 --> 01:37:58.860
everyone here [inaudible]
they can't seem to relate you

01:37:58.860 --> 01:38:01.770
because it ain't life and death.

01:38:01.770 --> 01:38:03.270
I mean, as a sense of purpose
[inaudible] the only gain

01:38:03.270 --> 01:38:04.570
in town.

01:38:04.570 --> 01:38:09.120
Only thing that make life
worth living back home,

01:38:09.120 --> 01:38:10.420
they're not [inaudible]
combat, I mean we talk

01:38:10.420 --> 01:38:13.530
about fire fights, we
dream about fire fights!

01:38:13.530 --> 01:38:16.990
I don't think I'll
ever be satisfied

01:38:16.990 --> 01:38:20.180
with a normal life
whatever that is,

01:38:20.180 --> 01:38:21.480
I think I'm ruined
for everything else.

01:38:21.480 --> 01:38:22.840
War, war is a lot of things but
let me tell you, it is useless

01:38:22.840 --> 01:38:24.140
to pretend exciting
isn't one of them,

01:38:24.140 --> 01:38:25.440
it is fucking insanely
exciting, the sounds it makes,

01:38:25.440 --> 01:38:26.890
the machinery of it, the urgency
of it's use, the consequences

01:38:26.890 --> 01:38:28.540
of almost everything about it's
the most exciting things anyone

01:38:28.540 --> 01:38:29.840
engaged in war has
ever experienced.

01:38:29.840 --> 01:38:31.140
We've talked about this
stuff with our friends

01:38:31.140 --> 01:38:32.440
with our families, they'll
never know, they'll never know.

01:38:32.440 --> 01:38:33.740
War is bad, but let me tell you,

01:38:33.740 --> 01:38:35.040
holding a 50-caliber
machine gun is amazing!

01:38:35.040 --> 01:38:36.340
War is life multiplied by some
number you've never even heard

01:38:36.340 --> 01:38:37.640
of, 20 minutes of
combat is more life

01:38:37.640 --> 01:38:38.940
than you can scrape
together in a lifetime

01:38:38.940 --> 01:38:40.240
of doing something else.

01:38:40.240 --> 01:38:41.540
I know it's sad but being
back home is boring!

01:38:41.540 --> 01:38:42.840
There's an aliveness when you're
in combat, everything is living,

01:38:42.840 --> 01:38:44.140
like this intense quiet, all
you hear is your footsteps,

01:38:44.140 --> 01:38:45.870
I'd be firing my saw

01:38:45.870 --> 01:38:48.300
[ Shoots ]

01:38:48.300 --> 01:38:50.590
OH men, this is it baby!

01:38:50.590 --> 01:38:52.510
This is combat!

01:38:52.510 --> 01:38:53.990
Everything is living!

01:38:53.990 --> 01:38:56.870
You're never more alive
until you're almost dead.

01:38:56.870 --> 01:38:59.170
War is hell but it's
also mysterious

01:38:59.170 --> 01:39:02.110
and beautiful for
all its horror.

01:39:02.110 --> 01:39:04.270
War makes you a man
but it's crazy

01:39:04.270 --> 01:39:06.080
because I know once I go
back I'll be all depressed

01:39:06.080 --> 01:39:10.120
and then I come back here and
all I can think about is war.

01:39:10.120 --> 01:39:14.400
Is like I have, like
a I have a mistress.

01:39:14.400 --> 01:39:19.610
I've got my wife which is love

01:39:19.610 --> 01:39:26.510
and this hot sexy dangerous
mistress which is war baby!

01:39:26.510 --> 01:39:29.510
[ Screams ]

01:39:29.510 --> 01:39:53.090
[ Screams and Music ]

01:39:53.090 --> 01:39:58.500
He's going to come
back, how do I know?

01:40:01.300 --> 01:40:03.860
I just know.

01:40:08.040 --> 01:40:10.340
Can I promise?

01:40:13.870 --> 01:40:21.560
Of course, I can promise, your
daddy loves you very much.

01:40:25.570 --> 01:40:30.080
I miss him a lot and my
son really misses them,

01:40:30.080 --> 01:40:34.970
we have to give up so
much for him to go back --

01:40:41.040 --> 01:40:43.970
This is going to be his
third tour in Afghanistan.

01:40:47.790 --> 01:40:50.500
When dinner rolls around and I
start thinking about what I have

01:40:50.500 --> 01:40:54.800
to make for dinner, I forget
that Mike is leaving us today

01:40:54.800 --> 01:41:02.040
and then afterwards
we're going have to sit

01:41:02.040 --> 01:41:04.200
at the dinner table alone.

01:41:04.200 --> 01:41:08.390
The first night is
always the hardest.

01:41:08.390 --> 01:41:10.570
You have this little one who
is moving all your emotions

01:41:10.570 --> 01:41:13.550
and you're trying to act

01:41:13.550 --> 01:41:16.470
like everything is OK
even though you don't feel

01:41:16.470 --> 01:41:21.400
like it's OK.

01:41:21.400 --> 01:41:22.870
He misses a lot of
events in our life,

01:41:22.870 --> 01:41:26.930
events that we can't get back,
so we think of creative ways

01:41:26.930 --> 01:41:32.990
to keep him with us, and one of
the ways was Mike on a stick,

01:41:32.990 --> 01:41:38.230
we're taking this picture that
you put on a Popsicle stick.

01:41:38.230 --> 01:41:41.310
I know it's weird, it's
definitely when will we go

01:41:41.310 --> 01:41:42.610
to a restaurant, so we ask Mike

01:41:42.610 --> 01:41:45.220
if my son can have
chicken tenders.

01:41:45.220 --> 01:41:47.720
The waiters always looked
at us like we belong

01:41:47.720 --> 01:41:57.970
in in a psych ward or something
but, it helps it really helps.

01:42:02.350 --> 01:42:12.970
I miss him a lot, but my son,
my son really has a hard time.

01:42:22.340 --> 01:42:32.040
I miss my daddy so much,
he misses all my events

01:42:34.850 --> 01:42:41.500
in my life like, like
when I became a week low,

01:42:44.400 --> 01:42:46.880
a lot of my friends who don't
know about the military just

01:42:46.880 --> 01:42:49.770
from what they see
in movies and stuff

01:42:49.770 --> 01:42:52.370
like that they think
it's kind of cool

01:42:52.370 --> 01:42:58.650
that my dad wears a uniform and
fires guns and stuff like that.

01:42:58.650 --> 01:43:08.750
But it's really hard to say bye
to daddy, I miss him so much.

01:43:08.750 --> 01:43:13.770
Hey don't tell anybody, OK?

01:43:13.770 --> 01:43:19.100
Because I don't know if
this is legal but I'm trying

01:43:19.100 --> 01:43:25.320
to invent a machine that
can hook my daddy up to

01:43:25.320 --> 01:43:30.510
so that he never
goes away again.

01:43:30.510 --> 01:44:01.710
[ Music ]

01:44:01.710 --> 01:44:13.000
This is my son Jeff, he was a
real of the real fun-loving boy,

01:44:13.000 --> 01:44:19.870
a real social boy,
clown real rascal.

01:44:19.870 --> 01:44:23.200
"Jeff, would you please
stop jumping off the couch?

01:44:23.200 --> 01:44:25.530
Yes, I know you can fly like
Superman, but I don't want you

01:44:25.530 --> 01:44:31.130
to do it in the living room".

01:44:31.130 --> 01:44:35.610
You really enjoyed life.

01:44:35.610 --> 01:44:41.400
I'm often asked if I
had the opportunity

01:44:41.400 --> 01:44:44.570
to trade the mental wound that
he suffer in Iraq for the bullet

01:44:44.570 --> 01:44:47.660
that he didn't receive,
would I trade it?

01:44:50.230 --> 01:44:51.530
I don't know.

01:44:51.530 --> 01:44:55.100
I just hated to see him
suffer the way you did.

01:44:55.100 --> 01:44:56.730
I remember when he came
back I really thought

01:44:56.730 --> 01:45:02.330
that that was a new chapter,
that was a new beginning for him

01:45:02.330 --> 01:45:04.180
but soon, after he came back,

01:45:04.180 --> 01:45:05.820
I realize that he was
far from unscathed.

01:45:05.820 --> 01:45:09.370
That the wounds he didn't
understand, was starting

01:45:09.370 --> 01:45:15.560
to terrify him and the rest of
us, his, his body had returned

01:45:15.560 --> 01:45:17.630
but that wasn't our boy anymore.

01:45:17.630 --> 01:45:22.090
He had become someone we've
never even seen before.

01:45:22.090 --> 01:45:24.930
It was on the first
anniversary of the Iraq War.

01:45:24.930 --> 01:45:28.180
He and his girlfriend were
supposed to go to Vermont

01:45:28.180 --> 01:45:33.410
to celebrate and for some reason
they had a tremendous fight

01:45:33.410 --> 01:45:37.640
and he became really
depressed and he came back home

01:45:37.640 --> 01:45:38.940
and he stayed with us.

01:45:38.940 --> 01:45:41.830
And he was sitting in the
living room staring at the fire

01:45:41.830 --> 01:45:44.000
in the fireplace, I'd
go up to him and say,

01:45:44.000 --> 01:45:47.380
"son let's go let's go to
the VA and get some help"

01:45:47.380 --> 01:45:53.560
and he always reply with
"I can't go Dad, I'm sorry,

01:45:53.560 --> 01:45:58.330
I just can't go, nothing matters
to me anymore I'm sorry, sorry".

01:45:58.330 --> 01:46:07.120
He was so terrified of the
stigma he didn't want his unit

01:46:07.120 --> 01:46:15.830
to see him as weak, that night
he came to me he asked me if,

01:46:15.830 --> 01:46:18.410
if you can sit in my lap and if
we can rock together like we did

01:46:18.410 --> 01:46:20.710
when he was a little boy.

01:46:23.430 --> 01:46:26.360
I felt lost and I felt
confused, but I said,

01:46:26.360 --> 01:46:32.560
"of course you can son,
of course you can".

01:46:32.560 --> 01:46:40.080
So, here I had this
marine, sitting in my lap

01:46:40.080 --> 01:46:48.530
and I told him how much I
loved him and how much I,

01:46:48.530 --> 01:46:53.890
how proud I was of him
and I begin to rock him,

01:46:53.890 --> 01:47:02.280
and it felt natural
holding my little boy again.

01:47:05.890 --> 01:47:08.640
I thought he was coming
back to us that night.

01:47:08.640 --> 01:47:10.360
We both went to bed
and I slept peacefully

01:47:10.360 --> 01:47:12.270
for the first time
in a long time.

01:47:12.270 --> 01:47:20.840
You know, when your little ones
grow up, they never really grow

01:47:20.840 --> 01:47:23.000
up I mean you worry about
them the same way you did

01:47:23.000 --> 01:47:27.440
when they were first born.

01:47:27.440 --> 01:47:29.840
The next morning I went to
his room to knock on the door

01:47:29.840 --> 01:47:36.480
and the door was locked,
"hey Jeff open up son,

01:47:36.480 --> 01:47:46.940
Jeff open the door" that would
be the last time I would hold

01:47:46.940 --> 01:47:50.920
my son.

01:47:50.920 --> 01:47:57.030
Would I ask if he would
have a, a quicker death?

01:47:57.030 --> 01:47:59.040
I would have just asked
him to have a good life.

01:47:59.040 --> 01:48:03.790
I remember at the funeral
cursing God "why did you give it

01:48:03.790 --> 01:48:08.140
to us if you were going to
let him suffer so much?"

01:48:08.140 --> 01:48:09.700
I wish I could put my
arms around him and say,

01:48:09.700 --> 01:48:11.870
"Son let's go, get some
help, not only for you

01:48:11.870 --> 01:48:16.290
but for the both of us".

01:48:16.290 --> 01:48:20.920
So, now what's happened is
we become his, his voice,

01:48:20.920 --> 01:48:23.870
and we don't do it in anger and
what happens a lot of families

01:48:23.870 --> 01:48:26.270
and come up to us and said
we don't want to be like you,

01:48:26.270 --> 01:48:29.340
we don't want to be grieving
parents so we tell them

01:48:29.340 --> 01:48:30.670
about the mistakes we made

01:48:30.670 --> 01:48:36.180
and tell him how hard it is
how hard it's going to be

01:48:36.180 --> 01:48:37.480
and there's going to be days

01:48:37.480 --> 01:48:40.230
when you feel you can't
do anything right, but,

01:48:40.230 --> 01:48:43.570
but don't give up don't
ever, ever, ever, give up.

01:48:43.570 --> 01:48:47.910
And don't think for a
second they won't do it.

01:48:47.910 --> 01:48:53.640
My greatest sin as a
father was thinking

01:48:54.810 --> 01:49:01.740
that Jeff wouldn't commit
suicide, not my boy.

01:49:08.510 --> 01:50:51.130
[ Music ]

01:50:51.130 --> 01:50:53.430
Shit, this is hard.

01:50:58.210 --> 01:51:01.190
There's a lot of things you take
for granted in life, you know?

01:51:01.190 --> 01:51:08.210
You don't know how valuable
something is until you lose it.

01:51:08.210 --> 01:51:11.990
When I lost my arm I
really wanted to die,

01:51:11.990 --> 01:51:16.460
I didn't know what my with
my wife would think of me,

01:51:16.460 --> 01:51:18.280
what my son would think of me.

01:51:18.280 --> 01:51:23.790
I felt like I let my
family down, you know?

01:51:23.790 --> 01:51:26.770
I couldn't be the
man I used to be.

01:51:26.770 --> 01:51:28.840
I sometimes I'll be
looking at my son wondering

01:51:28.840 --> 01:51:34.910
if he's thinking, "I don't
like the way my dad looks now".

01:51:34.910 --> 01:51:39.030
The hardest thing about losing
a limb is how you see yourself

01:51:39.030 --> 01:51:44.050
in the mirror, you have this
image that you're trying to see

01:51:45.110 --> 01:51:49.290
but when you look in there
he's not there anymore he's,

01:51:49.290 --> 01:51:51.840
he's, he's gone.

01:51:57.470 --> 01:52:01.440
One of the things that
I found really hard was,

01:52:03.390 --> 01:52:05.730
when I came back I really
thought it was going to be

01:52:05.730 --> 01:52:09.200
like a, you know,
a nice sunny day,

01:52:09.200 --> 01:52:11.520
the marine corps band was going
to be playing, it was going

01:52:11.520 --> 01:52:16.100
to be confetti and
silly strings.

01:52:16.100 --> 01:52:19.490
When I came back there was
nothing, nothing at all.

01:52:19.490 --> 01:52:21.990
And I didn't think it would
affect me, but it did, you know?

01:52:21.990 --> 01:52:23.290
It bothered me a lot.

01:52:23.290 --> 01:52:29.130
I used to be a pitcher in
college and I was good.

01:52:29.130 --> 01:52:30.780
It didn't matter if
it was a strikeout

01:52:30.780 --> 01:52:34.340
or a homerun I can focus on
the next pitch, you know?

01:52:34.340 --> 01:52:35.920
And that mental force
could serve me well

01:52:35.920 --> 01:52:37.220
on the battlefield.

01:52:37.220 --> 01:52:40.590
I mean, I found dozens of
IDs and I saved my brothers.

01:52:40.590 --> 01:52:47.940
But when I came back I
couldn't focus on anything, no.

01:52:54.150 --> 01:53:01.770
I keep getting these pains in my
left side, and I keep imagining

01:53:01.770 --> 01:53:04.020
in my arm is still there but
only like three inches long,

01:53:04.020 --> 01:53:06.750
which is freaking weird, because
not only did I lose my arm I

01:53:06.750 --> 01:53:10.380
keep imagining I got an
arm of an Elm or something.

01:53:10.380 --> 01:53:12.950
Everybody in rehab keeps
telling me this is normal;

01:53:12.950 --> 01:53:14.850
these are called
phantom limb pains.

01:53:14.850 --> 01:53:16.150
Well it may be normal for you

01:53:16.150 --> 01:53:19.510
but it's pretty freaking
weird to me man.

01:53:19.510 --> 01:53:23.390
Yes, when I came back I
[inaudible] around for weeks

01:53:23.390 --> 01:53:31.320
and months, but then my wife she
spoke some truth to me she said,

01:53:31.320 --> 01:53:35.480
"mira pendejo, I love you
with one arm or no arm,

01:53:35.480 --> 01:53:37.140
but if you don't get off
your ass and start fighting

01:53:37.140 --> 01:53:40.520
for your life, I'm
leaving your one arm ass".

01:53:40.520 --> 01:53:42.660
And you know what?

01:53:42.660 --> 01:53:46.960
She was right, she gave me the
kick in the balls that I needed.

01:53:46.960 --> 01:53:48.260
Stopped feeling sorry
for myself,

01:53:48.260 --> 01:53:51.340
start to understand how
I can fight and dominate

01:53:51.340 --> 01:53:52.740
in this world that
I now lived in.

01:53:52.740 --> 01:53:59.800
You see a lot of times we
think that our limitations are

01:53:59.800 --> 01:54:08.410
on the outside, pero no,
they're in the inside,

01:54:08.410 --> 01:54:09.880
life opens up when you focus

01:54:09.880 --> 01:54:12.970
on the possibilities
inside of you --

01:54:18.110 --> 01:54:22.510
And you stop making excuses.

01:54:22.510 --> 01:55:18.480
[ Music ]

01:55:18.480 --> 01:55:19.780
Hey Charlie, you got a light?

01:55:19.780 --> 01:55:26.520
I'm not the third one
on the match am I?

01:55:26.520 --> 01:55:33.760
Good, because I don't need any
more bad luck I got enough.

01:55:48.040 --> 01:55:54.970
Don't be scared Charlie it's
just a short walk over the top.

01:56:00.570 --> 01:56:02.600
Once we hear that whistle, we
climb out of these churches

01:56:02.600 --> 01:56:04.960
and we tumble over as
rapidly as we can and we run

01:56:04.960 --> 01:56:07.120
through the 30 yards
of wire entanglements,

01:56:07.120 --> 01:56:09.970
and we zigzag towards our enemy.

01:56:15.040 --> 01:56:16.880
It's a beautiful sight Charlie,

01:56:16.880 --> 01:56:22.120
when those German shells hit
the ground they shed a fantastic

01:56:22.120 --> 01:56:23.420
light upon this earth.

01:56:23.420 --> 01:56:29.670
Just imagine a vast
semi-circle of light shelling

01:56:29.670 --> 01:56:32.540
up every minute and
burning to 20 or 30 seconds

01:56:32.540 --> 01:56:35.150
and then [inaudible]
out like a rocket,

01:56:35.150 --> 01:56:38.410
lighting up every man tree
and bush within a half mile.

01:56:38.410 --> 01:56:41.850
The flashes in the sky and
the heavy claps of thunder

01:56:41.850 --> 01:56:44.970
from the unseen guns
create an amazing spectacle.

01:56:48.090 --> 01:56:50.480
It's like the 4th
of July Charlie.

01:56:50.480 --> 01:57:02.840
Soon we'll be at home
eating cherry pie.

01:57:02.840 --> 01:57:07.520
Hey Charlie, what's your
favorite part of a girl?

01:57:07.520 --> 01:57:11.400
Legs? Charlie, every
girl got legs.

01:57:11.400 --> 01:57:15.150
Me? Breast.

01:57:15.150 --> 01:57:21.700
I love a woman's breast Charlie,
my Mary has these big beauties,

01:57:21.700 --> 01:57:24.290
every time I smell her scent

01:57:24.290 --> 01:57:26.230
on those letters she writes
me I imagine my head right

01:57:26.230 --> 01:57:29.970
in the middle of them.

01:57:34.320 --> 01:57:35.880
I kiss my wedding ring
for good luck Charlie,

01:57:35.880 --> 01:57:40.960
it brings me back home and
back to my beautiful Mary.

01:57:59.070 --> 01:58:04.130
Stand up Charlie, let's go
fight dawn I'll be there

01:58:04.130 --> 01:58:09.830
by your side Charlie I promise.

01:58:09.830 --> 01:58:18.110
It's a short walk Charlie,
this is our great adventure,

01:58:18.110 --> 01:58:23.320
hey Charlie I want
you to know something,

01:58:23.320 --> 01:58:29.700
I'm the luckiest
fella in the world

01:58:29.700 --> 01:58:36.510
for I know is the true
meaning of what love is,

01:58:36.510 --> 01:58:41.140
[ Background noises ]

01:58:41.140 --> 01:58:45.340
Hey, you're my [inaudible]
Charlie,

01:58:45.340 --> 01:58:53.420
and I'll be with you
every step of the way,

01:58:53.420 --> 01:58:55.220
we fight for each other Charlie.

01:58:55.220 --> 01:59:02.510
[ Background noises ]

01:59:02.510 --> 02:00:05.040
[ Music ]

02:00:05.040 --> 02:00:12.980
Dear Sir, the indications are
strong that we shall be moving

02:00:12.980 --> 02:00:20.380
in a few days, perhaps tomorrow,
unless I should not be able

02:00:20.380 --> 02:00:24.480
to write you again and I feel
compelled to write a few lines

02:00:24.480 --> 02:00:27.270
that may fall under your
eyes when I shall be no more.

02:00:27.270 --> 02:00:34.290
If it is necessary that I
should fall on the battlefield

02:00:34.290 --> 02:00:40.930
to my country, I am ready.

02:00:40.930 --> 02:00:44.210
I have no misgivings or lack
of confidence, for the cause

02:00:44.210 --> 02:00:45.650
in which I am engaged.

02:00:45.650 --> 02:00:48.060
And my coach does not
halter falter [phonetic]

02:00:48.060 --> 02:00:51.110
for I know how strong
the American civilization

02:00:51.110 --> 02:00:54.300
that leans upon the
triumph of all government.

02:00:54.300 --> 02:00:59.520
And the great debt we owe
those who went before us.

02:00:59.520 --> 02:01:08.380
Through the blood and sufferings
of the American Revolution

02:01:08.380 --> 02:01:13.110
and I am willing, perfectly
willing, to lay down all my joys

02:01:13.110 --> 02:01:16.120
in this life to help
maintain this government

02:01:16.120 --> 02:01:20.970
and to pay that debt.

02:01:34.050 --> 02:01:36.000
So, my love for you is
absolutely deathless

02:01:36.000 --> 02:01:40.930
and it seems to find me with
[inaudible], and nothing

02:01:40.930 --> 02:01:42.290
but a [inaudible] can break.

02:01:42.290 --> 02:01:47.870
But my love my country comes
over me like a strong wind

02:01:47.870 --> 02:01:52.360
and bears me irresistibly
on into the battlefield.

02:01:57.090 --> 02:02:01.540
I cannot describe to you the
feelings on this column some

02:02:01.540 --> 02:02:04.800
of 2000 men sleeping around me,

02:02:04.800 --> 02:02:12.050
perhaps enjoying the last
before that of death.

02:02:12.050 --> 02:02:14.110
And I suspicious the death
is creeping behind me

02:02:14.110 --> 02:02:18.430
with a fatal [inaudible] and
communing with God country

02:02:18.430 --> 02:02:28.410
and the, the members of the
blissful moments I have spent

02:02:28.410 --> 02:02:32.100
with you come crawling over me
and I am grateful to God and you

02:02:32.100 --> 02:02:34.320
that I have enjoyed
it for so long.

02:02:34.320 --> 02:02:39.670
And it is hard for me to give
them up and to burn to ash

02:02:39.670 --> 02:02:41.680
at the hopes in the future years

02:02:41.680 --> 02:02:43.200
when God willing we might
have lived and loved

02:02:43.200 --> 02:02:46.820
to see our sons grow
up to be honorable man.

02:02:53.610 --> 02:03:01.320
I have few but, small's
claims on Divine Providence.

02:03:04.870 --> 02:03:10.670
But something whispers to me,
perhaps is the walking prayers

02:03:10.670 --> 02:03:12.410
of my little Edgar
that I shall return

02:03:12.410 --> 02:03:16.590
to my loved ones unharmed.

02:03:16.590 --> 02:03:20.600
But if I do not Sir, never
forget how much I love you

02:03:20.600 --> 02:03:24.510
and when my last breath
escapes me on the battlefield,

02:03:24.510 --> 02:03:26.880
I shall whisper your name.

02:03:30.430 --> 02:03:34.230
There'll be a soft breeze
pressed upon your cheek,

02:03:34.230 --> 02:03:38.800
that should be my spirit
passing by and kissing you.

02:03:44.550 --> 02:03:57.510
Do not mourn me Sir, wait for
me, for we shall meet again.

02:03:57.510 --> 02:05:18.920
[ Drums ]

02:05:18.920 --> 02:05:24.500
My final lesson was brotherhood.

02:05:27.010 --> 02:05:29.780
We are we at the
memorial service for Adam,

02:05:29.780 --> 02:05:33.280
Adam was struck by an IED and
was killed in Afghanistan.

02:05:33.280 --> 02:05:40.020
We had this guy in the battalion
that can play the bagpipes

02:05:40.020 --> 02:05:42.630
and our start major found
out so unfortunately for him,

02:05:42.630 --> 02:05:43.930
he had to pay the bagpipe

02:05:43.930 --> 02:05:46.460
out every memorial we
had in Afghanistan.

02:05:46.460 --> 02:05:49.630
But it was a blessing for us
because he was really good

02:05:49.630 --> 02:05:52.440
at it, and there's
something extraordinary moving

02:05:52.440 --> 02:05:56.210
and beautiful about
the sound of a bagpipe.

02:05:56.210 --> 02:05:58.740
And if you're not
Irish or Scottish,

02:05:58.740 --> 02:06:04.430
for those brief moments
you kind of wish you were.

02:06:06.710 --> 02:06:11.010
Adam had attended ranger school,
and he had been there for 7

02:06:11.010 --> 02:06:14.950
or 8 months and he was about
to finish, but he got dropped.

02:06:14.950 --> 02:06:16.630
And if anyone knows anything
about the Ranger tag,

02:06:16.630 --> 02:06:18.600
it's a pretty coveted
tab to have,

02:06:18.600 --> 02:06:20.850
if you get it you can ask
anybody that doesn't have it.

02:06:20.850 --> 02:06:25.420
And if you don't get
it well, you get past.

02:06:25.420 --> 02:06:27.070
At the memorial service
for Adam everyone

02:06:27.070 --> 02:06:29.820
who was Ranger qualified as
they walked by his picture

02:06:29.820 --> 02:06:33.280
to say their final goodbyes
and make the final salutes.

02:06:33.280 --> 02:06:35.120
They all took off to the
Ranger tag and placed

02:06:35.120 --> 02:06:38.730
on the memorial for Adam.

02:06:38.730 --> 02:06:43.560
Sort of as a, as a
recognition that he was more

02:06:43.560 --> 02:06:46.000
than just another
guy who got killed.

02:06:48.910 --> 02:06:52.310
And at that moment you realize
that it's not about you anymore,

02:06:52.310 --> 02:06:58.150
it's about your country
but more importantly it's

02:06:58.150 --> 02:07:01.990
about the men you serve with.

02:07:01.990 --> 02:07:09.030
When I hear taps now I can feel
it, it means something to me.

02:07:09.030 --> 02:07:12.040
I realized, I realize
now that I'm part

02:07:12.040 --> 02:07:18.510
of an amazing history I'm
part of a brotherhood.

