02:12:01.640 --> 02:12:03.750
&gt;&gt; Can you share a little
bit about your history

02:12:03.750 --> 02:12:05.220
as an actor, as an artist?

02:12:05.220 --> 02:12:06.520
&gt;&gt; Douglas Taurel: Sure.

02:12:06.520 --> 02:12:07.820
Well I'm a professional actor,

02:12:07.820 --> 02:12:11.790
I've been doing it
for many moons now.

02:12:11.790 --> 02:12:15.510
You probably recognize me on
TV I do a lot of, I play a lot

02:12:15.510 --> 02:12:18.800
of cop and a lot of
Hitman type roles on TV.

02:12:18.800 --> 02:12:21.580
Theater is my passion,
I love it.

02:12:21.580 --> 02:12:28.380
I've been doing it in New York
for 20 years now and, but yes,

02:12:28.380 --> 02:12:34.680
I mean, I have a movie coming
out with Meghan Gyllenhaal,

02:12:34.680 --> 02:12:38.420
"The kindergarten teacher", I
play a cop in there with her.

02:12:38.420 --> 02:12:43.970
So, those serious sensibilities
tend to draw me so,

02:12:43.970 --> 02:12:45.430
I'm funny when I'm drinking

02:12:45.430 --> 02:12:49.020
but I never get cast
as a comedy guy.

02:12:49.020 --> 02:12:54.130
And so, but yes, I mean,
not to spit off my resume

02:12:54.130 --> 02:12:56.080
but that's who I am as an actor.

02:12:56.080 --> 02:12:58.940
But I love the stage,
is for my training.

02:12:58.940 --> 02:13:00.240
I've been really blessed to work

02:13:00.240 --> 02:13:01.540
with some amazing
theater people.

02:13:01.540 --> 02:13:07.880
I work with, I study with Win
Hanuman, he was kind of the,

02:13:07.880 --> 02:13:10.790
the, the nucleus of my acting
as an actor here in New York.

02:13:10.790 --> 02:13:15.030
He's legendary, he's, he's,
he's worked with everybody

02:13:15.030 --> 02:13:19.130
from Dustin Hoffman
to, to Al Pacino.

02:13:19.130 --> 02:13:21.600
I mean, who's the
who's of actors,

02:13:21.600 --> 02:13:25.000
and his classes were really
great because we always worked

02:13:25.000 --> 02:13:27.320
on character and you had to
do a monologue and you had

02:13:27.320 --> 02:13:30.820
to create this guy or this
girl or whatever, and,

02:13:30.820 --> 02:13:34.320
and you had to find the
dialect in the behavior in the

02:13:34.320 --> 02:13:35.690
with everything about them.

02:13:35.690 --> 02:13:39.800
So, his training really led me
into this type of work because,

02:13:39.800 --> 02:13:41.700
in many ways this
is what I'm doing.

02:13:41.700 --> 02:13:44.480
I'm finding out who the
guy is, how does he talk,

02:13:44.480 --> 02:13:47.730
how does he walk,
what, what are his his,

02:13:47.730 --> 02:13:49.930
his, his speech patterns.

02:13:49.930 --> 02:13:52.710
And so, it's character work, so
that's really where my training

02:13:52.710 --> 02:13:54.010
and he's Meisner based.

02:13:54.010 --> 02:13:55.480
I don't know if anybody else
know anything about acting

02:13:55.480 --> 02:13:57.440
but he's very Meisner based.

02:13:57.440 --> 02:14:04.130
But yes, that he's pretty
much whom I owe my acting to.

02:14:04.130 --> 02:14:09.140
Yes Austin, that's my son.

02:14:09.140 --> 02:14:14.130
He asked another question,
what did you say son?

02:14:14.130 --> 02:14:16.510
Jesus Christ I'm
going to kill you.

02:14:16.510 --> 02:14:21.050
[ Laughter ]

02:14:21.050 --> 02:14:24.050
A lot of shows son,
I've been in True West.

